(globalThis.TURBOPACK||(globalThis.TURBOPACK=[])).push(["object"==typeof document?document.currentScript:void 0,69020,(e,t,i)=>{t.exports=JSON.parse('[{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","title":"Purpose of Life and Health Insurance (Unit 1)","sections":[{"heading":"Fundamentals of Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurance exists to answer one question: \\"Who pays when something goes wrong?\\" Rather than one person bearing the full financial weight of a death, injury, or illness, insurance lets a large group share the burden. This idea rests on two pillars."},{"type":"list","items":["**Risk pooling** (loss sharing) — a group of people each contributes a small amount into a common fund. When one member suffers a loss, the fund pays. The loss shifts from one person to many, making it manageable for everyone.","**Law of large numbers** — a mathematical principle: the larger the group of similar risks combined, the more accurately an insurer can predict future losses. A pool of 100,000 similar-age drivers gives far better loss predictions than a pool of 50. This predictability is what makes insurance commercially viable."]},{"type":"tip","text":"If the exam asks \\"what gives insurance its certainty,\\" the answer is the **law of large numbers**. If it asks \\"what spreads the financial burden,\\" the answer is **risk pooling**. They work together but test differently."}]},{"heading":"Risk: The Two Classes","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Risk** in insurance means uncertainty regarding financial loss. Not all risk is insurable — you need to know which kind is which."},{"type":"list","items":["**Speculative risk** — involves the chance of loss, no change, OR gain. Think gambling, investing in the stock market, or starting a business. Because there\'s a potential for profit, speculative risks are NOT insurable.","**Pure risk** — involves only the chance of loss or no loss, with no possibility of gain. An injury from an accident is pure risk: you won\'t profit if it doesn\'t happen, and you lose if it does. Only pure risks are insurable."]},{"type":"p","text":"Insurance is not designed for the insured to profit — it restores the insured to the same financial condition they were in before the loss. This concept is called **indemnity**."},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide uses the ARRT mnemonic for risk handling (Avoid, Reduce, Retain, Transfer), but the exam often frames the question as: \'Purchasing insurance is the most effective way of ______ risk.\' The answer is always **transferring**. **Risk retention** is also called **self-insuring**."}]},{"heading":"Perils and Hazards","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"A **peril** is the cause of a loss. In life insurance, the peril is death. In health insurance, the peril is sickness or injury. A **hazard** is a condition that increases the likelihood of a loss occurring."},{"type":"list","items":["**Physical hazard** — a tangible condition that increases risk: icy walkways, broken stairs, wet floors, a person\'s poor health or dangerous occupation.","**Moral hazard** — arises from character defects like dishonesty. A person who files false insurance claims or commits arson for insurance money presents a moral hazard.","**Morale hazard** — arises from carelessness or indifference because one has insurance. Smoking, not wearing a helmet, or leaving doors unlocked because \\"insurance will cover it\\" are morale hazards."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide groups moral and morale hazards together, but the exam draws a sharp distinction. **Moral** = intentional dishonesty (fraud). **Morale** = carelessness (indifference). A classic exam trap is listing both and asking which involves dishonesty — that\'s **moral hazard**."}]},{"heading":"Handling Risk","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"There are four methods of handling risk, remembered with the mnemonic **ARRT**:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Risk avoidance** — eliminating the exposure entirely. If you never go skydiving, you avoid the risk of a skydiving injury. Not always practical.","**Risk reduction** — taking steps to lower the probability or severity of loss. Installing a car alarm reduces theft risk. Wearing a seatbelt reduces injury severity.","**Risk retention** — accepting the financial responsibility yourself. Choosing a high deductible or not buying insurance at all means you retain risk. Also called **self-insuring**.","**Risk transference** — shifting the financial risk to another party. Buying insurance is the primary example — the insurer assumes the financial risk in exchange for premium payments."]},{"type":"tip","text":"On the exam, remember that insurance is always classified as **risk transference**, never risk reduction. Installing sprinklers reduces risk; buying a fire policy transfers it. If both are answer choices, pick the one that matches the question\'s wording."}]},{"heading":"Elements of Insurable Risk","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Not every risk is insurable. For a risk to qualify as insurable, it must meet six criteria:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Fortuitous (chance)** — the loss must be accidental and outside the policyholder\'s control. Intentional losses are not insurable.","**Definite and measurable** — the loss must be definite as to cause, time, place, and amount so the insurer can quantify it.","**Statistically predictable** — the insurer must be able to use statistics to predict the frequency and severity of losses.","**Not catastrophic** — the risk must have thresholds at which insurers can expect losses to stop. Wars and widespread floods typically fail this test.","**Large number of similar exposure units** — the insurer needs a large pool of similar risks to apply the law of large numbers.","**Randomly selected** — the group covered and the exposures must be chosen at random to prevent adverse selection."]},{"type":"tip","text":"A popular exam question: \'Which of the following does NOT constitute an insurable risk?\' The answer is typically \'the loss must be catastrophic\' — because insurability requires the loss to be **non-catastrophic**. Watch the wording carefully."}]},{"heading":"Adverse Selection","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Adverse selection** is the tendency of higher-risk individuals to seek insurance more actively than lower-risk individuals. A person who knows they have a health condition is more motivated to buy health insurance than a perfectly healthy person. Left unchecked, adverse selection would flood the insurance pool with high-risk applicants, driving up costs for everyone."},{"type":"p","text":"Insurers combat adverse selection through **underwriting** — evaluating each applicant\'s risk profile and assigning appropriate premiums or declining coverage when the risk is too great."},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide defines adverse selection but doesn\'t explain the remedy. The exam asks: \'How do insurers control adverse selection?\' The answer is **underwriting**."}]},{"heading":"Human Life Value","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Human life value** is a person\'s economic worth measured by the total future earnings that would have been devoted to their family. When determining how much life insurance a person needs, the human life value approach calculates the present value of the income stream the family would lose if the breadwinner died."},{"type":"tip","text":"The **needs approach** is the other common method for calculating life insurance needs — it adds up what the family would actually need (mortgage payoff, education funds, living expenses) rather than projecting lost income. Know both for the exam, but the study guide emphasizes **human life value**."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["What are the two fundamental principles of insurance and how do they work together?","Can you explain the difference between speculative and pure risk — and which is insurable?","What\'s the difference between a peril, a physical hazard, a moral hazard, and a morale hazard?","Name the four methods of handling risk using the ARRT mnemonic.","Which elements must a risk have to be insurable? Which element is the most common \'trick\' answer?","How do insurers combat adverse selection?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","title":"The Insurance Industry (Unit 2)","sections":[{"heading":"Types of Insurers","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurance is provided by three broad categories of organizations: **private insurers**, **government insurers**, and **self-insurers**. Private insurers come in many forms, and the exam expects you to know the ownership and profit structures of each."},{"type":"list","items":["**Stock insurers** — owned by stockholders (shareholders) who invest capital and share in profits. Policyholders are customers only. Stock companies are **nonparticipating** — policyholders do not receive dividends.","**Mutual insurers** — owned by the policyholders themselves. Because the policyholders are also the owners, mutual companies are **participating** — they may pay dividends (a return of surplus premium) to policyholders.","**Reciprocal insurers** — similar to mutuals in that policyholders own the company, but here the policyholders insure each other. A reciprocal is managed by an **attorney-in-fact** who makes decisions on behalf of the members.","**Lloyd\'s of London** — not an insurer itself, but a marketplace that brings together individuals who form **syndicates** to underwrite insurance. Lloyd\'s gathers underwriting information and helps settle claims. It provides coverages that might be unavailable elsewhere.","**Reinsurers** — specialized companies that provide insurance for other insurance companies. The reinsurer takes on risk from the **ceding company** (the original insurer), helping the ceding company manage large exposures.","**Risk Retention Group (RRG)** — a mutual insurance company formed by members of the same business, occupation, or profession (e.g., pharmacists, dentists, engineers) to insure their shared risks.","**Fraternal benefit societies** — nonprofit organizations with a lodge system and ritualistic activities, governed by elected officials. They are known for charitable work and provide insurance as a member benefit.","**Home service (debit) insurers** — specialize in **industrial insurance**: small face-amount policies (usually $1,000–$2,000) with premiums collected weekly in person by the selling agent."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The **stock vs. mutual** distinction is the most-tested insurer question. Stock = shareholders own it, nonparticipating. Mutual = policyholders own it, participating (may receive dividends). If the exam says \'owned by its policyholders,\' the answer is **mutual**."}]},{"heading":"Service Providers","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Unlike commercial insurers that reimburse the insured for covered expenses, **service providers** deliver benefits in the form of actual services rendered by participating hospitals and physicians. Subscribers pay premiums for the services, not insurance — an important legal distinction."},{"type":"list","items":["**HMO (Health Maintenance Organization)** — provides a range of healthcare services for a set prepaid fee. Subscribers must use in-network providers contracted with the HMO. HMOs emphasize preventive care.","**PPO (Preferred Provider Organization)** — a network of providers offering services at negotiated, discounted rates. Members can go out-of-network but pay more. No referral needed for specialists."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide doesn\'t fully distinguish how service providers differ from commercial insurers on the exam. Key point: **service providers** sell health care services, not insurance. If a question asks \'which entity sells services rather than insurance,\' the answer is a service provider like an HMO."}]},{"heading":"Government Insurers","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Federal and state governments provide what is referred to as **social insurance** programs funded by taxes. These programs serve national and state social purposes rather than operating for profit."},{"type":"list","items":["**Social Security (OASDI)** — provides old-age, survivors, and disability insurance benefits. Funded through FICA payroll taxes.","**Medicare** — federal hospital insurance (Part A) and supplemental medical insurance (Part B) for people aged 65+, those receiving Social Security disability, and those with chronic kidney disease.","**Medicaid** — a joint federal and state program that provides coverage for low-income individuals including children, pregnant women, seniors, individuals with disabilities, and certain indigenous populations."]},{"type":"tip","text":"**Medicare** is federal. **Medicaid** is federal AND state. The exam loves this distinction. Medicare is based on age/disability, not income. Medicaid is based on financial need. A person who is blind but not poor does not qualify for Medicaid."}]},{"heading":"Self-Insurers","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Rather than purchasing an insurance policy, a **self-insurer** establishes its own reserves to cover possible losses. Large companies often self-insure employee health benefits because they have enough employees to spread the risk internally. The key risk is that the self-insurer retains all financial responsibility — if claims exceed reserves, the organization absorbs the loss."}]},{"heading":"How Insurance Is Sold","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Licensed **producers** sell the majority of insurance. An **agent** represents the insurer; a **broker** represents the buyer. Agents fall into two main categories: **captive (career) agents** who work for one company exclusively, and **independent agents** who represent multiple companies."},{"type":"list","items":["**Career agency system** — career agencies are divisions of major stock and mutual insurers. Agents are contracted to represent one insurer in a particular territory.","**Personal Producing General Agency (PPGA) system** — similar to a career agency, but agents are managed by PPGA regional directors and treated as PPGA employees rather than insurance company employees.","**Independent agency system** — agents represent multiple insurance companies through individual contracts and are compensated by commission or fee. The independent agent owns the book of business (client list), not the insurer."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide mentions but doesn\'t emphasize this: in Florida, there is no separate **broker license**. To act as a broker, you must hold another license (like a life or health license). The exam may reference this distinction."}]},{"heading":"History of Insurance Regulation","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Understanding why insurance is regulated at the state level requires knowing a few landmark events and laws:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Paul v. Virginia (1869)** — the Supreme Court ruled that insurance was NOT interstate commerce and therefore was subject only to state regulation.","**US v. South-Eastern Underwriters Association (1944)** — the Supreme Court reversed course and ruled that insurance IS interstate commerce and could be regulated by the federal government.","**McCarran-Ferguson Act (1945)** — Congress responded by declaring that states should continue to regulate insurance, as long as state laws were adequate. Federal antitrust laws apply only when state regulation is insufficient. This is the foundation of modern state-based insurance regulation.","**Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act (1999)** — a federal law protecting consumer financial privacy. Requires insurers to establish safeguards for customer records, protect against threats to their security, and prevent unauthorized access.","**Fair Credit Reporting Act (1970)** — requires fair and accurate reporting of consumer information. Insurers must inform consumers of the investigating agency\'s name if an application is denied or rates are increased. Violations can result in punitive damages.","**USA PATRIOT Act (2001)** — gives federal agencies powers to combat money laundering and terrorism financing. Requires insurers to create compliance systems, designate anti-money laundering officers, and implement rigorous identity verification."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The exam loves the timeline: **Paul v. Virginia** (state regulation) → **South-Eastern Underwriters** (federal can regulate) → **McCarran-Ferguson** (states continue). Remember: McCarran-Ferguson did NOT remove federal power — it said states get to regulate unless their laws are inadequate."}]},{"heading":"State Regulation of Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurance companies doing business in any state must be licensed by that state. Companies are classified by where they are incorporated:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Domestic insurer** — incorporated in the state where it is doing business.","**Foreign insurer** — incorporated in another US state but licensed to do business in this state.","**Alien insurer** — incorporated in a country other than the United States."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The terminology is relative to the state asking. Company ABC incorporated in New York is a **domestic** insurer in New York but a **foreign** insurer in Florida. If incorporated in Canada and selling in any US state, it\'s an **alien** insurer."}]},{"heading":"Insurance Producers and Licensing","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"In Florida, the agent\'s license is **perpetual** — it does not expire on a fixed date — unless it is suspended or revoked by the state. However, **continuing education (CE)** requirements must still be met."},{"type":"list","items":["Agents licensed **1–5 years**: 20 hours of CE every 2 years.","Agents licensed **more than 5 years**: 24 hours of CE every 2 years."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide lists 20 hours for newer agents and 24 for experienced ones. Watch the exam question — it may specify the agent\'s tenure. Also note: in Florida the license is **perpetual**, not renewable on a fixed cycle like many other states."}]},{"heading":"Industry Associations and Rating Services","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**NAIC (National Association of Insurance Commissioners)** — a nonprofit organization of state insurance regulators. Its four objectives: (1) preserve state (not federal) regulation of insurance, (2) promote consistency in state insurance laws, (3) promote administrative efficiency, (4) protect policyowner/consumer interests. The NAIC also developed the **Advertising Code**, which specifies misleading words and phrases that insurers may not use.","**Unfair Trade Practice Act** — adopted by state legislatures, this act empowers the chief financial officer (in Florida) to investigate insurers and producers, issue cease-and-desist orders, and impose penalties.","**Guaranty associations** — support insurance companies and consumers when an insurer becomes insolvent by covering policyholder claims, up to statutory limits.","**NAIFA** and **NAHU** — professional associations that support life and health insurance industries and work to advance the quality of service provided by insurance professionals.","**Rating services** — **A.M. Best**, **Standard & Poor\'s**, **Moody\'s**, and **Fitch** publish guides to insurers\' financial strength, stability, and claims-paying ability. These ratings help consumers and other insurers assess an insurer\'s financial integrity."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The NAIC does NOT make laws or regulate insurers directly — it\'s a model-law body and coordination forum. Individual states adopt (or don\'t) its model laws. **A.M. Best** is the rating service most frequently referenced on insurance exams."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["What\'s the ownership difference between a stock insurer and a mutual insurer?","Which type of insurer is managed by an attorney-in-fact?","Name the three systems that support insurance sales through agents and brokers.","What three terms describe an insurer based on where it was incorporated?","What did the McCarran-Ferguson Act establish, and what court case prompted it?","What are the four objectives of the NAIC?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","title":"Law and the Insurance Contract (Unit 3)","sections":[{"heading":"Elements of a Valid Contract","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"For any contract — including an insurance contract — to be legally binding, four elements must be present. In addition, insurance contracts require **insurable interest**."},{"type":"list","items":["**Offer and acceptance** — the applicant makes an offer to buy insurance by submitting an application and (usually) an initial premium. The insurer accepts the offer by issuing the policy. The application plus initial premium together constitute the offer.","**Consideration** — something of value exchanged. The applicant\'s consideration is the premium payment and the statements made on the application. The insurer\'s consideration is the promise to pay benefits according to the contract terms.","**Legal purpose** — the contract must be for a lawful objective. Insurance is considered to possess a legal purpose.","**Competent parties** — both sides must be legally capable of entering a contract. The insurer is competent if authorized (licensed) by the state. The applicant is competent unless they are: (1) a minor (under age 15 in Florida — note this is lower than the typical age 18 in most states), (2) mentally infirm, or (3) under the influence of drugs or alcohol."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Florida\'s age of competency for insurance contracts is **15**, not 18. This is a favorite exam question. Also note: the applicant\'s consideration includes BOTH the premium AND the statements on the application — not just the money."}]},{"heading":"Special Features of Insurance Contracts","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurance contracts differ from ordinary commercial contracts in several important ways. The exam tests each of these distinctions heavily."},{"type":"list","items":["**Aleatory** — there is an element of chance, and the dollar amounts exchanged may be unequal. An insured might pay $300 in premiums and receive a $200,000 death benefit. Both parties accept this unequal exchange.","**Contract of adhesion** — the insurer alone writes the contract; the applicant either accepts it as written or rejects it. Because the applicant has no power to negotiate terms, any ambiguity in the contract is interpreted in favor of the insured.","**Unilateral** — only the insurer makes an enforceable promise. The insured is not legally obligated to continue paying premiums, but the insurer IS obligated to pay benefits if premiums have been paid and the loss occurs.","**Conditional** — certain conditions must be met before the insurer must perform. For example, premiums must be paid and proof of loss must be submitted.","**Contract of utmost good faith** — both parties must deal honestly and disclose all material facts. This concept encompasses warranties, representations, and concealment."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The **adhesion** principle is critical for the exam: because the insured had no say in drafting the contract, courts interpret ambiguous language against the insurer (the drafter) and in favor of the insured. If you see a question about who benefits from ambiguity, the answer is always the insured/policyowner."}]},{"heading":"Valued vs. Indemnity Contracts and Subrogation","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurance contracts are classified as either **valued** or **indemnity**, depending on how benefits are paid:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Valued contract** — pays a stated, predetermined amount when the covered event occurs, regardless of the actual financial loss. Life insurance is the classic valued contract: the policy pays the face amount at death, whether the insured was worth $50,000 or $5 million.","**Indemnity contract** — pays an amount equal to the actual loss, up to the policy limit. Property insurance is the classic example: a $100,000 policy on a home that suffers $12,000 in damage pays only $12,000.","**Subrogation** — a feature built into indemnity contracts. After paying a claim, the insurer gains the insured\'s right to pursue any negligent third party that caused or contributed to the loss. Subrogation prevents the insured from collecting twice (once from the insurer, once from the responsible party)."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide doesn\'t stress this, but the exam does: **subrogation** applies to indemnity contracts (property, health) but generally does NOT apply to valued contracts (life insurance). You cannot \\"subrogate\\" a death benefit."}]},{"heading":"Warranties, Representations, and Concealment","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"These three concepts are conditions of **utmost good faith** — they represent ways a contract can be challenged:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Warranty** — the applicant\'s statement is guaranteed to be absolutely true. If a warranty turns out to be false, even innocently, the insurer may void the contract. Warranties are rare in life and health insurance; they are more common in property insurance.","**Representation** — a statement made by the applicant believed to be true to the best of their knowledge. Representations need only be substantially true. However, a **material misrepresentation** (one that would have changed the insurer\'s underwriting decision) can be grounds for voiding the contract.","**Concealment** — the deliberate failure to disclose a known material fact. Concealment can void the contract if the hidden fact was material to the insurer\'s decision."]},{"type":"tip","text":"**Warranty** vs. **representation** is a top exam topic. Warranty = guaranteed true (strict standard). Representation = believed true (reasonable standard). On life and health policies, applicant statements on the application are almost always treated as **representations**, not warranties."}]},{"heading":"Insurable Interest and Personal Contracts","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Insurable interest** means the person obtaining the policy must face a genuine financial loss from the insured event. Without insurable interest, a policy is void from the start."},{"type":"list","items":["In **life insurance**, insurable interest must exist at the time of application — NOT at the time of death. A person always has insurable interest in their own life. Close family members (spouses, parents, children) and business partners are presumed to have insurable interest.","In **health and property insurance**, insurable interest must exist at the time of loss.","Life insurance is NOT a **personal contract** — it is freely assignable. The owner is called a **policyowner** (not policyholder) because ownership can be transferred through **assignment** without the insurer\'s prior consent."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide mentions **STOLI (Stranger-Originated Life Insurance)** — where third-party investors persuade individuals to take out policies with the investor as beneficiary. STOLI is problematic because when the policy originates, the investor has no insurable interest in the insured\'s life. Most states prohibit or restrict STOLI arrangements."}]},{"heading":"The Concept of Agency","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Agency law** defines the relationship between the insurer (principal) and the agent. An agent\'s actions are legally the actions of the principal. A contract completed by the agent is a contract of the principal. Payments made to the agent are payments made to the principal. Information the agent possesses is presumed to be knowledge of the principal."},{"type":"list","items":["**Express authority** — authority specifically set out in writing in the agent\'s contract (appointment). Express authority is what the insurer explicitly allows the agent to do.","**Implied authority** — authority not written in the contract but assumed because it\'s necessary to carry out the agent\'s express duties. For example, an agent authorized to sell policies can implicitly accept applications.","**Apparent authority** — authority that exists because the public reasonably believes the agent has it, based on the agent\'s actions or the insurer\'s representations. If a company gives an agent business cards and an office, customers may reasonably assume the agent has authority to bind coverage."]},{"type":"tip","text":"**Express** = in the contract. **Implied** = not in the contract but reasonably assumed. **Apparent** = not in the contract but the public believes it based on appearances. The exam may describe a scenario and ask which type of authority applies."}]},{"heading":"Fiduciary Duty","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"A **fiduciary** is any person who holds a position of trust and confidence. An insurance agent acts as a fiduciary when accepting premiums or offering advice that affects a person\'s financial security. To fulfill fiduciary obligations, an agent must be fit and proper, demonstrate honesty and trustworthiness, maintain a favorable business reputation, be competent, understand and adhere to state laws, and act in good faith."},{"type":"p","text":"In Florida, there is no separate broker license. A broker must hold another active license (such as a life license). Agents represent the insurer; brokers represent the buyer — but both owe fiduciary duties."},{"type":"tip","text":"**Errors and Omissions (E&O) insurance** is professional liability insurance that protects the agent against lawsuits arising from professional mistakes. The study guide mentions it briefly, but the exam may ask what kind of insurance protects an agent from claims of professional negligence — the answer is **E&O**."}]},{"heading":"Other Legal Concepts","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Waiver** — the voluntary giving up of a legal right. If an insurer knowingly waives a policy condition (like accepting late premium payments without objection), it cannot later enforce that condition.","**Estoppel** — a legal principle that prevents (estops) a party from asserting a right that contradicts their prior actions. If an insurer\'s actions led the insured to reasonably believe they were covered, the insurer may be estopped from denying the claim.","**Parol evidence rule** — when parties put an agreement in writing, prior oral statements cannot be used to modify or contradict the written contract. The written policy is the entire agreement.","**Void contract** — has no legal effect from the beginning; it was never valid (e.g., a contract for an illegal purpose).","**Voidable contract** — a valid contract that can be legally rejected by one party with the right to do so. For example, a minor\'s contract is voidable at the minor\'s option.","**Fraud** — fraud in an insurance contract can void the contract, but only if a material fact was misrepresented. The insurer typically has a limited time (usually 2 years from issue) to challenge the contract. After that **incontestability period**, the insurer generally cannot contest the contract or deny benefits."]},{"type":"tip","text":"**Void** vs. **voidable** is a classic exam distinction. Void = never valid, no contract ever existed. Voidable = valid until the party with the right to void it exercises that right. A contract obtained by fraud is typically **voidable**, not void — because it was valid until the fraud was discovered."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Name the four elements required for a valid contract, plus the additional requirement for insurance.","What is the age of competency for insurance contracts in Florida?","What characteristic of an adhesion contract benefits the insured?","What\'s the difference between a valued contract and an indemnity contract? Give an example of each.","Name the three types of agent authority and give an example of each.","Explain the difference between a void contract and a voidable contract."]}]}]},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","title":"Licensure, Ethics, and the Insurance Producer (Unit 4)","sections":[{"heading":"Ethical Business Practices","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Ethics**, **compliance**, and **market conduct** are three related but distinct concepts. Understanding the differences is essential for both the exam and professional practice."},{"type":"list","items":["**Compliance** — conducting business according to current rules and laws set by regulatory agencies or the government. Compliance is the legal floor: it\'s what you must do.","**Ethics** — standards of conduct and moral frameworks for decision-making. Ethical behavior goes beyond compliance: being honest, loyal, fair, compassionate, acting with integrity, showing respect, and taking personal accountability.","**Market conduct** — a combination of ethics and compliance. It refers to how insurers and producers actually behave in the marketplace, including how they interact with customers and follow regulations."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The exam sometimes offers scenarios where an action is legal but unethical — or ethical but not required by law. **Compliance** is about legality; **ethics** is about doing the right thing even when the law doesn\'t specifically require it. **Market conduct** bridges both."}]},{"heading":"The Producer\'s Duties","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"The insurance producer owes duties to three parties: the **principal** (insurer), the **policyowner/client**, and the **public**. These duties often overlap but each has specific expectations."},{"type":"list","items":["**Duties to the principal (insurer)** — the agent owes honesty, loyalty, and hard work to protect the principal from liability.","**Duties to the policyowner** — the agent must obtain and maintain the knowledge and skills needed for problem analysis, action planning, product recommendation, and plan implementation. The two most important commitments are: (1) knowledge and skills, and (2) educating the prospect or client about the product.","**Policy delivery** — when a policy is issued as applied for, the producer must promptly deliver it and review its features and benefits with the new policyowner. Important: in Florida, **electronic policy delivery is NOT allowed** for life insurance policies and annuity contracts.","**Duties to the public** — insurance companies and producers must provide the public with fair and honest representation of policies and services. Services before, during, and after the sale are as important as selling the product."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide emphasizes that the **insurer** is the producer\'s primary responsibility during the application process. This sounds counterintuitive — shouldn\'t it be the client? But legally, the producer is an agent of the insurer (the principal), and the principal relationship comes first in terms of legal duty."}]},{"heading":"Presenting Recommendations and Full Disclosure","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"The foundation of every product presentation is **full disclosure** — educating the client and providing complete details about the product. **Deceptive sales presentations** generate the most complaints from the public. A deceptive sale occurs when a presentation misleads a prospect, lacks full disclosure, or includes misleading or unclear product comparisons."},{"type":"list","items":["**Policy illustrations** — hypothetical projections showing how a policy will perform over time. They give the client expectations about premiums, benefits, and cash values. Best practices include: use realistic assumptions, clearly distinguish guaranteed from nonguaranteed values, encourage the applicant to ask questions, and review the illustration together.","**Avoiding misrepresentation** — producers should avoid: overstating promises and guarantees, making false claims that values are guaranteed, using false figures or deceptive information, giving statements not supported by the policy, and committing intentional fraud.","The term **\'vanishing premiums\'** has been used in the past and is considered misleading — avoid using it."]},{"type":"tip","text":"If the exam asks \'what is the cornerstone of a product presentation,\' the answer is **full disclosure**. If it asks what generates the most public complaints, the answer is **deceptive sales practices**."}]},{"heading":"Policy Replacement","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Policy replacement** — canceling an existing policy to buy a new one — should be approached with extreme caution. The study guide advises: avoid replacement unless you cannot in good conscience leave a policy as it is. Replacement can expose the client to significant financial loss or risk."},{"type":"list","items":["**Health and age changes** — the client may now be uninsurable or face higher premiums due to age or health changes since the original policy was issued.","**New contestable period** — the insurer\'s window to challenge claims starts over with the new policy, exposing the client to a new 2-year contestability period.","**New policy fees and expenses** — front-loaded costs on the new policy could take two years or more for the client to break even.","**Loss of improvements** — many companies introduce upgrades to existing policies; replacement forfeits these.","**Loss of grandfathered rights** — older policies may have tax or regulatory advantages that new policies don\'t.","**Documentation requirements** — Florida replacement rules require the agent to provide the applicant with a **Notice Regarding Replacement** and proper comparative disclosures."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Policy replacement questions on the exam often test whether you recognize the downsides. The exam may describe a situation and ask whether replacement is appropriate. Red flags include: the client is now older/less healthy, the new policy has a new **contestable period**, or the agent\'s primary motivation appears to be commissions."}]},{"heading":"Prohibited Practices","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurance law prohibits several specific practices that harm consumers. These are among the most heavily tested topics on the licensing exam."},{"type":"list","items":["**Misrepresentation** — providing false or inaccurate information to an insurance company or to the public about a policy\'s benefits, provisions, or terms.","**Defamation** — spreading false rumors, written or verbal, about a competing producer or the financial condition of another insurance company.","**Rebating** — giving the buyer a portion of the agent\'s commission (or anything of value not specified in the policy) to induce a purchase. In Florida, rebating is permitted only if: all insureds in the same actuarial class are eligible, the rebate follows a filed schedule, the schedule is uniformly applied and prominently displayed, the agency does not prohibit rebates, and prohibited risk factors (age, sex, race, ethnic origin, marital status) are not used to determine the rebate percentage.","**Twisting** — illegally inducing an insured to cancel an existing policy to purchase a comparable policy from another insurer. Twisting involves misrepresentation.","**Churning** — replacing policies internally within the same company, often by the same producer who sold the original, primarily to generate new commissions at the client\'s expense.","**Coercion** — using physical or mental force, or the threat of force, to persuade someone to buy or transact insurance.","**Unfair discrimination** — making distinctions between individuals of the same underwriting classification that are not justified by actuarial data. Charging different premiums to two people with identical risk profiles is unfair discrimination."]},{"type":"tip","text":"**Twisting** vs. **churning** is a top exam question. Twisting = replacing with a DIFFERENT company (external replacement through misrepresentation). Churning = replacing within the SAME company (internal replacement for commissions). Both are illegal, but the distinguishing factor is whether the replacement is external or internal."}]},{"heading":"License Suspension and Termination","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"The state insurance department can take action against producers who violate insurance laws:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Suspension** — a temporary measure prohibiting the producer from conducting insurance business for a specific period. The license can be restored after the suspension ends.","**Termination (revocation)** — a permanent revocation of the producer\'s license. The producer must reapply and meet all requirements to be re-licensed."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Know that **suspension** is temporary and **revocation** is permanent. If the exam describes an agent committing a serious offense like misappropriating premium funds, the likely penalty is license **revocation** (termination), not just suspension."}]},{"heading":"Documentation, Client Service, and Ethical Responsibilities","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Documentation** — every meeting and transaction between the client and the agent must be documented. Thorough records protect both the agent and the client.","**Client service** — routine follow-up calls should be made to ensure the client\'s needs are still being met. Client calls for services or information should be given priority. Complaints should be handled promptly and fully.","**Needs-based selling** — the agent\'s ethical responsibility is to ensure the client\'s needs are met, not to sell the policy that generates the biggest commission.","**Authorized insurer** — an agent should verify that an insurer is authorized to do business in the state, because only the obligations of licensed insurers are covered by the state **guaranty fund**. If an unauthorized insurer fails to pay claims, clients have no safety net."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The **MIB (Medical Information Bureau)** is a database that collects medical and personal information on insurance applicants. Insurers use MIB data during underwriting to verify applicant statements and detect undisclosed conditions. The exam may ask what resource insurers use to check applicant medical history — the answer is the **MIB**."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["What is the difference between compliance, ethics, and market conduct?","Name the two most important commitments a producer owes to the policyowner.","What is the cornerstone of a product presentation?","Name at least four reasons why policy replacement may harm a client.","What is the difference between twisting and churning? Between rebating and coercion?","Under what conditions is rebating permitted in Florida?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","title":"Introduction to Health Insurance (Unit 15)","sections":[{"heading":"What Health Insurance Is","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Health insurance** protects people against the financial consequences of sickness and injury. Where life insurance answers \\"what happens to my family\'s finances if I die?\\", health insurance answers \\"what happens to my finances if I get sick or hurt and either rack up medical bills or can\'t work?\\" Everything in this unit builds on three basic types of coverage."},{"type":"list","items":["**Medical expense insurance** — pays the actual costs of medical care: hospitalization, surgery, physician services, treatment programs, outpatient care. Medicare supplement and long-term care policies for the elderly also fall under this umbrella.","**Accidental death and dismemberment (AD&D)** — pays a lump sum if the insured dies in an accident or loses a limb or eyesight. It\'s usually sold as part of a group plan and is considered the purest form of accident insurance because it pays only for accidents, never sickness.","**Disability income insurance** — replaces a portion of lost income when the insured can\'t work due to disability. Key trap: it does NOT pay the medical bills caused by the disability — only the lost paycheck."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Mnemonic: **MAD** — Medical expense, AD&D, Disability. Exam questions love to offer a fake fourth type (like \\"limited pay health\\") and ask which one is NOT a basic form of health insurance."}]},{"heading":"How Health Insurance Is Purchased","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Coverage reaches people through three channels. **Individual policies** are contracts issued directly between one insured and a commercial insurer or service organization — you pick the policy, you pay the premium, the contract is yours. **Group coverage** is issued as a single **master contract** to an employer, association, or other group; members receive **certificates of coverage** rather than individual policies. **Government programs** fill the gaps: **Medicaid** is the state-run program for low-income people, while the federal government provides **Medicare** and the disability provisions of **OASDI** (Social Security)."},{"type":"tip","text":"Keep the jurisdiction straight: **Medicaid** = state (for the needy), **Medicare** and **OASDI** = federal. This distinction shows up repeatedly on the exam."}]},{"heading":"Renewability: How Secure Is Your Policy?","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"A **renewability provision** defines the insurer\'s right to cancel or refuse to renew a policy. The five classifications form a ladder — each step up gives the insured more security and costs more in premium."},{"type":"list","items":["**Cancellable** — the insurer can cancel at any time with notice and a refund of unearned premium. Least protection, least expensive.","**Optionally renewable** — the insurer may refuse to renew, but only at a renewal or anniversary date.","**Conditionally renewable** — the insurer may refuse to renew only for specific reasons stated in the contract (never for deteriorating health).","**Guaranteed renewable** — the insurer MUST renew the policy, but may raise premiums for an entire class of insureds (never for one individual).","**Noncancellable** — the insurer must renew AND can never raise the premium. Maximum protection, most expensive."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Cheapest to priciest = least secure to most secure. If a question says the insurer must renew but can raise rates by class, that\'s **guaranteed renewable**. If rates can never change, that\'s **noncancellable**."}]},{"heading":"Premiums: Modes and Pricing Factors","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"The **premium mode** is how often the policyowner pays: annually, semiannually, quarterly, monthly, or weekly. Paying annually carries the lowest total cost, because the insurer earns interest on the money and bills you once. Each step toward more frequent payment adds billing expense and lost interest, so weekly is the most expensive way to pay overall."},{"type":"p","text":"Four factors go into calculating a health insurance premium:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Morbidity** — the expected rate of sickness and injury in a population. This is health insurance\'s counterpart to life insurance\'s **mortality**, and it\'s the factor unique to health insurance.","**Interest** — what the insurer expects to earn investing premiums before claims are paid.","**Expense** — the insurer\'s cost of doing business (underwriting, administration, commissions).","**Types of benefits** — richer benefits, higher premium."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Mnemonic: **MIX-T** — Morbidity, Interest, eXpense, Types of benefits. If the exam asks which premium factor is unique to health insurance versus life insurance, the answer is **morbidity**."}]},{"heading":"Participating vs. Nonparticipating","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Individual** health policies are typically **nonparticipating** — no dividends, the price is the price. **Group** health policies are typically **participating**: policyholders may receive dividends (a refund of premium from a mutual insurer) or **experience-rating refunds** when the group performs well. Whether anything gets paid back comes down to two factors: the insurer\'s expenses and the group\'s claims costs. A group with low claims earns a premium credit or refund; a group with high claims doesn\'t."},{"type":"tip","text":"Individual = **nonparticipating**. Group = **participating**. Dividends are a return of premium — and the two factors that determine whether they\'re payable are expenses and claims costs."}]},{"heading":"Reserves and How Claims Are Paid","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Insurers set aside **reserves** to make sure money exists to pay future claims. Reserves are a liability on the insurer\'s books — they represent money owed, not money earned. There are two kinds: **premium reserves** cover potential losses that haven\'t happened yet but for which premium has already been collected, and **loss reserves** cover claims that have already occurred but haven\'t been fully settled or paid."},{"type":"p","text":"How a policy pays a claim splits the insurance world into two camps. Medical expense insurance is a **contract of reimbursement** (the indemnity approach) — it pays based on the actual amount of loss, no more. Life insurance, AD&D, and disability income are **valued contracts** — they pay a predetermined, stated amount when the covered event occurs, regardless of actual financial loss. A disability policy promising \\"$350 per month while totally disabled\\" is a valued contract."}]},{"heading":"The Affordable Care Act","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"The **ACA** reshaped the individual health market. The numbers below are heavily tested."},{"type":"list","items":["**Premium subsidies** — available to individuals and families with income between 100% and 400% of the **Federal Poverty Level**.","**Medicaid expansion** — eligibility extended to nearly everyone at or below 138% of the poverty level, including childless adults. Undocumented immigrants are not eligible.","**Preexisting conditions** — insurers may not deny coverage based on preexisting conditions (children were protected first, six months after enactment, then everyone).","**Dependent coverage** — children may stay on a parent\'s plan until age 26.","**Individual mandate** — everyone was required to carry health insurance starting in 2014 or pay a $695 annual tax. The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act zeroed out the tax beginning in 2018, but the mandate itself technically remains on the books.","**Employer mandate** — employers with 50 or more full-time employees must offer qualifying coverage to at least 95% of full-time employees and their dependents, or face a penalty of $2,000 per worker per year if any worker takes federal assistance to buy insurance."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Memorize the figures: **100–400% FPL** for subsidies, **138%** for Medicaid expansion, **age 26** for dependents, **50 employees / 95% / $2,000** per worker for the employer mandate, **$695** for the (now zeroed) individual mandate tax."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Can you name the three basic types of health coverage and what each pays for?","Which renewability class lets the insurer raise premiums by class but never refuse renewal?","Which premium factor exists in health insurance but not life insurance?","Is a disability policy paying a flat monthly benefit a valued or reimbursement contract?","What income range qualifies for ACA subsidies, and what threshold applies to expanded Medicaid?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","title":"Health Insurance Providers (Unit 16)","sections":[{"heading":"Commercial Insurers","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Commercial insurance companies** — monoline carriers, casualty companies, and life and health companies, including debit (home service) businesses — sell health insurance on the **reimbursement approach**: the insured receives medical care, submits the bills, and the insurer pays the insured back. Most policies include a **right of assignment**, which lets the insured direct the insurer to pay the medical provider directly, so the policyholder doesn\'t have to front the money. Assignment changes who receives the check, not the nature of the contract — it\'s still reimbursement."},{"type":"tip","text":"If a question asks which entity reimburses the insured directly for covered expenses, the answer is the **commercial insurer** — not an HMO, PPO, or service provider."}]},{"heading":"Service Providers: HMO, PPO, and POS","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Service providers** sell benefits rather than reimbursement — subscribers pay a premium and receive services. **Blue Cross Blue Shield** is the classic example: hospitals and physicians contract with BCBS at stipulated costs, and most BCBS customers today are in an affiliated HMO, PPO, or POS plan. When BCBS sells an HMO plan it is acting as a service provider, not an insurer."},{"type":"list","items":["**HMO (Health Maintenance Organization)** — both delivers and pays for care on a **prepayment** basis. Doctors are paid in advance, the plan emphasizes preventive care and early detection, you need a referral from your **primary physician (gatekeeper)** to see a specialist, and out-of-network care is not covered except in emergencies.","**PPO (Preferred Provider Organization)** — a network of doctors, hospitals, and clinics providing services at predetermined, discounted rates. Doctors are paid **fee-for-service** after the visit, no referral is needed for specialists, and out-of-network care IS covered — it just behaves like major medical, with a deductible and coinsurance.","**POS (Point of Service)** — a hybrid. Stay in network and it works like an HMO with the highest level of benefits; go out of network and it works like a PPO, with claim forms to file and higher cost-sharing."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Fast recall: **HMO** = prepaid, preventive, referral required, in-network only. **PPO** = fee-for-service, no referral, out-of-network allowed at higher cost. **POS** = HMO inside the network, PPO outside it."}]},{"heading":"Government Programs","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Medicare** — federally administered health insurance for people 65 and older, people receiving Social Security disability income benefits, and people with chronic kidney disease.","**Social Security disability income (SSDI)** — to qualify, a person must be physically or mentally incapable of performing ANY substantial gainful work, and the impairment must be expected to last at least 12 months or result in death. There is a **5-month waiting period**; benefits begin with the 6th month of disability.","**Medicaid** — aid for the needy, with no age requirement. It typically pays for low-income individuals who are blind, disabled, or under 21, and it is administered by the states with federal funding. Need is the test — a person who is blind but not poor does not qualify.","**Workers\' compensation** — state-mandated, compulsory benefits for workers who are injured, become ill, or die because of their job. The injured worker is entitled to benefits without filing a lawsuit. Employers can buy a policy from an insurer, self-insure, or buy into a state plan."]},{"type":"tip","text":"SSDI benefit-timing math is a favorite exam question. Disabled in July → wait August through December (5 months) → first benefit is for January, paid in February. Practice walking the months."}]},{"heading":"Self-Insurance, TPAs, and ASOs","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Instead of buying insurance, a business (or individual) can **self-insure** — set money aside and pay claims directly. The self-insured employer retains all the risk. Because handling claims is paperwork-heavy, self-insured businesses usually hire an outside firm to administer the plan: a **third-party administrator (TPA)**, or an insurance company providing **administrative services only (ASO)**. The administrator processes claims but takes on no risk and uses no actuaries — the employer\'s money pays every claim."},{"type":"p","text":"To protect against a catastrophic year, many self-insured employers add a **minimum premium plan (MPP)**, which backstops the program against large, unanticipated losses."}]},{"heading":"Direct Primary Care Agreements","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"A **direct primary care agreement** is a written contract between a primary care physician and a patient (or the patient\'s legal agent or employer) under which the patient pays the doctor directly for primary care services. Both parties must sign the written agreement for it to be valid. Two things it is NOT: it is not insurance, and it does not satisfy the ACA\'s minimum essential coverage requirement. It also does not indemnify for services rendered by third parties — it covers only what that physician provides."}]},{"heading":"METs and MEWAs","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Small employers often can\'t get good group rates alone, so they pool together."},{"type":"list","items":["**Multiple Employer Trust (MET)** — multiple employers pool their employees into one trust to buy lower-cost coverage. The trust holds the funds and holds the master contract; each employer must join the trust as a member. A MET can be self-funded or can purchase a plan from an insurance company.","**Multiple Employer Welfare Arrangement (MEWA)** — a type of MET in which small employers in the same industry (or related industries) collaborate to offer health benefits. Employees must share an employment-related common bond, and the arrangement is tax-exempt."]},{"type":"p","text":"Because METs and MEWAs behave like insurance products, both are regulated by the state."},{"type":"tip","text":"**MET** = any employers pooling through a trust that holds the master contract. **MEWA** = same-industry employers with a common bond, tax-exempt. Both: state-regulated."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Which provider type reimburses the insured, and which provides services instead?","Name three ways an HMO differs from a PPO.","Who qualifies for Medicare? For Medicaid? Who administers each?","When does an SSDI benefit actually arrive for someone disabled in March?","In a self-insured plan with a TPA, who retains the risk?","What\'s the difference between a MET and a MEWA, and who regulates them?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","title":"Medical Expense Insurance (Unit 17)","sections":[{"heading":"The Two Worlds of Medical Expense Coverage","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Medical expense insurance pays the costs of medical care — hospital care, diagnostics, lab work, rehab, dental, physical therapy. Every plan falls into one of two categories: **basic** plans (limited, first-dollar coverage) and **major medical** plans (broad, catastrophic coverage). Most plans pay on a **reimbursement** basis (actual expenses incurred); some pay a **fixed rate** (a flat amount per day, regardless of actual cost)."},{"type":"tip","text":"Clue words for MAJOR MEDICAL on the exam: major, comprehensive, reimbursement, flat deductible, right of assignment, commercial insurer. Clue words for BASIC: first dollar, benefit limits, no deductible."}]},{"heading":"Basic Medical Expense Plans — First Dollar Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Basic plans are called **first dollar insurance** because they pay from the first dollar with no deductible. The trade-off: low benefit LIMITS. Basic plans control costs by capping benefits — not with deductibles or coinsurance. The five coverage categories:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Basic hospital expense** — daily room and board (room charges, meals, general nursing) up to a daily limit, plus **miscellaneous expenses**: drugs, X-rays, anesthesia, lab fees, dressings, operating room, supplies. Miscellaneous limits are often expressed as a multiple of the daily room-and-board benefit. NOT covered: surgeons\' fees and physicians\' bedside visits — those belong to surgical and physicians\' expense coverage.","**Basic surgical expense** — surgeon, anesthesiologist, and post-operative care, paid by one of three methods (next section).","**Basic physicians\' (non-surgical) expense** — office visits and other non-surgical physician services.","**Nurses\' expense** — private duty nursing.","**Convalescent care expense** — skilled nursing facility costs."]},{"type":"tip","text":"\'What does the miscellaneous expense benefit NOT cover?\' — room and board, physicians\' bedside visits, and the ANESTHESIOLOGIST\'S professional services. Anesthesia the substance IS covered as miscellaneous — \'the administering of anesthesia\' is the trap wording. \'What limits miscellaneous expenses?\' — they\'re tied to the daily room-and-board benefit. Basic plans also never cover LOST INCOME — that\'s disability insurance."}]},{"heading":"The Three Surgical Payment Methods","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Surgical schedule** — the insurer assigns a flat dollar value to each procedure. If the schedule says $500 and the surgeon bills $675, the policy pays $500.","**Reasonable and customary (R&C)** — the charge is compared to what\'s typical for that REGION. Anything above R&C is the patient\'s responsibility.","**Relative value scale** — each procedure gets POINTS, converted to dollars by a **conversion factor**. Example: an appendectomy worth 60 points with a $10 conversion factor pays 60 × $10 = $600."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Points = relative value scale. Dollar amounts per procedure = surgical schedule. Geographic comparison = reasonable and customary. Practice the points × conversion factor math."}]},{"heading":"Major Medical: Supplementary vs. Comprehensive","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Supplementary major medical** — sits ON TOP of a basic plan: covers what the basic plan excludes and expenses that exceed the basic plan\'s limits.","**Comprehensive major medical** — ONE policy covering almost all medical costs, combining basic + major medical protection."]},{"type":"p","text":"Major medical plans carry large benefit limits (lifetime dollar limits are now prohibited by the ACA) and use two cost-sharing tools that keep premiums down: the **deductible** and **coinsurance**. The ACA also eliminated preexisting-condition exclusions in ACA-compliant plans — historically those exclusions protected insurers from adverse selection."}]},{"heading":"The Three Major Medical Deductibles","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Flat** — a fixed sum (e.g., $500) the insured pays first. Expenses below the deductible mean the policy pays nothing.","**Corridor** — works WITH a basic policy: the basic plan pays first; once its benefits are exhausted, the insured pays the full deductible (the \'corridor\') before major medical benefits begin.","**Integrated** — the deductible can be satisfied (offset) in whole or part by what the basic plan pays."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Three deductibles: flat, corridor, integrated. STOP-LOSS IS NOT A DEDUCTIBLE — it\'s a separate feature. \'Which is not a major medical deductible?\' → stop-loss. Deductibles are most common in MAJOR MEDICAL plans, never basic plans."}]},{"heading":"Coinsurance, Stop-Loss, and the Math","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"After the deductible, insurer and insured split costs — most commonly **80/20**. Coinsurance discourages overutilization of benefits. The **stop-loss feature** caps the insured\'s out-of-pocket: past that point, the insurer pays 100%. Stop-loss applies to the COINSURANCE share."},{"type":"p","text":"**Worked example:** $9,500 hospital bill, $500 deductible, 80/20 coinsurance. Insured pays $500 + 20% of the remaining $9,000 ($1,800) = **$2,300**. The insurer pays $7,200."},{"type":"p","text":"**Basic plan example:** policy pays $50/day room and board (insured hospitalized 7 days at $80/day), $500 scheduled surgery (billed $675), $750 miscellaneous max (billed $800). Policy pays 7×$50 + $500 + $750 = **$1,600** — every benefit capped at its limit, the rest is the insured\'s problem."},{"type":"tip","text":"Deductible first, then the percentage of what REMAINS. For basic plans, pay each category only up to its stated limit."}]},{"heading":"HDHPs and the Three Accounts","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**HDHP** — high deductible, low premium; the entry ticket for an HSA.","**HSA (Health Savings Account)** — individually owned, tax-favored savings for medical costs; requires HDHP enrollment, no other first-dollar coverage, not on Medicare. Funds roll over and are portable.","**FSA (Flexible Spending Account)** — EMPLOYEE pretax contributions for out-of-pocket medical costs; use-it-or-lose-it.","**HRA (Health Reimbursement Account)** — EMPLOYER-funded pretax dollars covering deductibles, copays, and coinsurance."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Who funds it: HSA = individual (needs HDHP). FSA = employee pretax. HRA = employer ONLY — \'HRAs are established by the employer\' is the tested fact."}]},{"heading":"Other Medical Expense Coverages","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Hospital indemnity (fixed-rate)** — pays a flat daily/weekly/monthly amount per day hospitalized, paid TO THE INSURED (not the hospital). Because the benefit is fixed, claim costs aren\'t affected by rising healthcare costs, premiums stay low, and underwriting is simple — which also makes it the premium least affected by medical inflation.","**Limited risk (dread disease) policies** — cover one specific ailment, like cancer or heart disease. Travel accident and hospital indemnity policies are also limited risk policies.","**Accident-only insurance** — covers accidents, never illness.","**Short-term medical** — covers a specific period; Florida defines it as coverage expiring less than 12 months after the effective date, not exceeding 36 months total with renewals."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Fixed-rate plan questions: benefits go to the INSURED, not the hospital — \'benefits are paid directly to the hospital\' is the NOT-true answer. Dread disease = cancer policy = limited risk."}]}]},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","title":"Disability Income Insurance (Unit 18)","sections":[{"heading":"Purpose: Insuring Against Economic Death","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Disability income insurance protects against the **economic death** of a wage earner — being alive but unable to earn. Benefits are paid as income payments (at minimum **monthly**), sized either by a formula tied to a **percentage of pre-disability earnings** or as a **flat amount**. Policies cover accidents only, or sickness and accidents together."},{"type":"list","items":["**Occupational coverage** — covers disabilities that happen ON or off the job.","**Nonoccupational coverage** — covers only disabilities occurring OFF the job (on-the-job injuries are workers\' comp territory). Most group DI is nonoccupational."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Disability insurance replaces a paycheck. It never pays hospital bills — and medical expense insurance never pays lost income. Keep the lanes separate."}]},{"heading":"Defining Total Disability","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Own occupation** — can\'t perform YOUR OWN job (the dentist who can\'t practice dentistry). Easiest to qualify under, most favorable to the insured, most expensive.","**Any occupation** — can\'t perform ANY job you\'re suited for by **education, training, or experience**. More restrictive, cheaper. Job INTEREST is never part of the test.","**Presumptive disability** — automatic qualification for full benefits: complete/substantial loss of sight, deafness, loss of speech, or loss of two or more limbs. Diseases like cancer are NOT presumptive disabilities — they must qualify under the policy\'s regular definition."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Occupational suitability = education, training, experience. \'Job interest\' is the planted wrong answer. Standard rule: any-occupation is the MORE restrictive definition — own-occupation the LESS restrictive one. CAUTION: this course\'s bank has keyed an identical question \'less restrictive\' — if you hit it on a course quiz and \'more restrictive\' is marked wrong, flag it to your instructor; the state-exam answer is MORE restrictive."}]},{"heading":"Partial and Residual Benefits","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Partial disability** — can work, but not full duties or full time. Paid either as a **flat amount** stated in the policy or…","**Residual amount** — a portion of ACTUAL INCOME LOST. A $1,000/month benefit with a 40% income loss pays **$400/month**; a $2,500 benefit with the same 40% loss pays **$1,000**.","A doctor who returns part-time and keeps receiving proportional benefits is using a **residual benefit clause**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Residual math: benefit × percentage of income lost. It is never \'benefit minus salary\' or a flat 50%."}]},{"heading":"Accidental Means vs. Accidental Bodily Injury","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Accidental means** (restrictive) — both the CAUSE and the result must be unexpected. Deliberately jumping into a lake and breaking your neck = the jump was intentional = NO coverage, regardless of how unintended the injury was.","**Accidental bodily injury** (broader) — only the RESULT must be unexpected. Accidentally falling off a cliff = covered."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Under accidental means, the insurer pays NOTHING for an intentional act with an unintended injury. If the question features a voluntary jump, the answer is \'pay nothing — the jump was no accident.\'"}]},{"heading":"The Policy\'s Time Machine: Probationary, Elimination, Benefit, Delayed","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Probationary period** — one-time window after issue (commonly **15 or 30 days**) during which SICKNESS is not covered. Accidents are covered immediately from day one.","**Elimination (waiting) period** — the \'time deductible\' after a disability begins, before benefits start. Benefits are NOT paid retroactively for the elimination period. Per this course\'s bank, the elimination period applies to **sickness only — accidents are payable immediately** (just like the probationary period; the book says it \'may apply only to sickness depending on the policy\'). Longer elimination = lower premium.","**Benefit period** — how long benefits last once they start. Longer benefit period = higher premium. The cheapest combination: LONG elimination period + SHORT benefit period.","**Delayed disability provision** — an injury from an accident may manifest later and still be covered, up to a maximum of **90 days** after the accident."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Two scenario traps: (1) Joseph, 30-day elimination period, sick 15 days → benefits NEVER paid; he recovered inside the elimination period. (2) Lucy, benefit to age 65 with a 6-month wait, disabled at 64½ → she reaches 65 as the wait ends and collects NOTHING."}]},{"heading":"Recurrent, Non-Disabling, and Elective Indemnity","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Recurrent disability** — if the same disability returns within the stated window (commonly 6 months), benefits RESUME immediately: no new elimination period. Rachel, disabled Jan 15–Apr 15 and again Sept 1 — benefits resume Sept 1.","**Non-disabling injury benefit** — an injury that doesn\'t stop you from working can still trigger payment of the ACTUAL COST OF MEDICAL TREATMENT, up to a limit. It never pays a salary percentage.","**Elective indemnity** — on some short-term policies, the insured may choose a LUMP SUM for certain named injuries instead of income payments."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Non-disabling injury benefit = actual medical treatment cost. Lump sum option for named injuries = elective indemnity."}]},{"heading":"Riders","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Waiver of premium** — no premiums owed during total and permanent disability; may apply retroactively; usually drops off at age 60 or 65. It belongs to DISABILITY income policies — saying it \'normally applies to both medical expense and disability income policies\' is FALSE.","**Social Security rider** — extra income while eligible for, but not yet receiving, Social Security benefits; coordinates with the government benefit.","**COLA rider** — benefit adjusts with the **Consumer Price Index** to keep pace with inflation.","**Guaranteed insurability rider** — buy additional coverage at predetermined intervals with no new evidence of insurability (DI increases are tied to an earnings test — you can\'t insure income you don\'t have)."]},{"type":"tip","text":"CPI in the question = COLA rider. Keep-the-policy-alive-while-disabled = waiver of premium. Buy-more-later-without-underwriting = guaranteed insurability."}]},{"heading":"Benefit Periods by Policy Type","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Individual **short-term disability** policies typically carry benefit periods from **six months to two years**. Long-term policies run two years, five years, to age 65, or for life. Whatever the length, individual disability claims must be paid no less frequently than **monthly**."}]}]},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","title":"Accidental Death & Dismemberment (Unit 19)","sections":[{"heading":"The Nature of AD&D","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"AD&D is classified as **pure accident insurance**: it pays a predetermined sum only when an accident causes death or the loss of body parts (hands, feet, or sight in one or both eyes). Sickness never triggers it — a $50,000 AD&D policy pays nothing if the insured dies of a heart attack. Because the amounts are predetermined, an AD&D policy is a **valued contract** (a policy of value), not a contract of indemnity."},{"type":"list","items":["**Principal sum** — the death benefit paid for accidental death. (Memory hook: the Principal is the head of the school — the full amount, paid at death.)","**Capital sum** — paid for dismemberment or loss of sight, usually a **percentage of the principal sum**. Losing one eye on a $100,000 policy might pay a $15,000 capital sum.","**Multiple indemnity** — some policies pay double, triple, or quadruple the principal sum when death occurs under specific circumstances (e.g., as a fare-paying passenger on a common carrier). A $40,000 triple-indemnity policy pays $120,000."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Principal sum = accidental DEATH benefit. Capital sum = DISMEMBERMENT benefit (a percentage of the principal). Swapping these two is the classic exam trap."},{"type":"list","items":["**90-day rule** — accidental death benefits pay only if death occurs within **90 days** of the accident (\'within 60 days\' is the planted wrong answer).","**Loss of use counts** — dismemberment benefits may be paid for permanent **loss of use** (Ed loses use of his right hand and arm = covered). Losing fingers without the whole hand does NOT count.","**Course-bank quirk**: when asked what each sum \'pays for,\' this bank keys the principal sum to **loss of life ONLY**, and puts ALL dismemberments — hands above the wrist, partial foot, an eye, all fingers — under the **capital sum** schedule."]}]},{"heading":"Accidental Means vs. Accidental Results","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Accidental means** — BOTH the cause and the outcome must be unintentional. You must have *fallen* off the ladder; if you *jumped* and got hurt, no benefit. The stricter, less favorable definition.","**Accidental results** (accidental bodily injury) — only the resulting injury must be unintentional. Jumping off the ladder and breaking a leg IS covered, because you didn\'t intend the injury. The broader, more favorable definition."]},{"type":"tip","text":"These definitions mean the same thing here as they did in disability income (Unit 18). \'Means\' = cause AND result accidental; \'results\' = only the result. Results = better coverage."}]},{"heading":"Other Forms of AD&D","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Limited risk policies** — cover death/dismemberment from one specific, named risk only (e.g., a round-trip **travel accident policy** bought at the airport, or skydiving coverage). Benefits pay only if the loss results from that named risk.","**Special risk policies** — cover unusual hazards ordinary policies won\'t touch: a professional violinist insuring her hands, a test pilot\'s exposure. Written for the specific person and hazard."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Airport travel-accident policy = LIMITED risk. Violinist\'s hands / unusual occupational hazard = SPECIAL risk."}]}]},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","title":"Government Health Insurance Programs (Unit 20)","sections":[{"heading":"Medicare Part A — Hospital (Compulsory)","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Medicare Part A is **compulsory** and financed by **FICA payroll taxes**. When a qualified individual applies for Social Security benefits, Part A is provided **automatically**. It pays for hospitalization and related care."},{"type":"list","items":["Covers: **inpatient hospital care**, **post-hospital skilled nursing facility care** (up to **100 days** per benefit period), **home health care**, and **hospice** for the terminally ill (including family support).","For the **first 60 days** of hospitalization, Part A pays **100% of covered services except the initial deductible**.","A **benefit period** begins on hospital admission and ends 60 days after discharge.","Beyond 90 days of hospitalization, patients draw on a **lifetime reserve of 60 additional hospital days** — once used, those reserve days are gone forever."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Numbers to memorize: deductible-only for the first 60 days; benefit period ends 60 days after discharge; 90 days per benefit period plus a 60-day lifetime reserve; 100 days of skilled nursing care."},{"type":"tip","text":"Part A costs: premium-FREE for anyone with 40 work quarters (others may buy in), but everyone pays the Part A deductible. CAUTION: a course-bank question marked \'the insured must pay a deductible\' wrong for Part A — likely keyed \'deductible and premium.\' Flag it to your instructor if you hit it; for the state exam, most people pay NO Part A premium but DO owe the deductible."}]},{"heading":"Medicare Part B — Medical (Voluntary)","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Part B is **voluntary** supplementary coverage — it is NOT compulsory. It covers doctors\' services, outpatient care, medical supplies, and preventive services.","Financed by **monthly premiums** (usually deducted from the Social Security check) — not by FICA.","The insured pays a monthly premium, an **annual deductible**, and **20% coinsurance**; after the deductible Medicare pays **80%** of approved charges. There is NO per-benefit deductible.","**Primary vs. secondary payor**: a working 65+ employee at an employer with **20 or more employees** keeps the employer plan as **primary** coverage; Medicare is **secondary**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Part A = compulsory, FICA-financed, automatic with Social Security. Part B = voluntary, premium-financed. \'Part B is compulsory\' is a planted wrong answer."}]},{"heading":"Parts C & D, and What Medicare Excludes","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Part C — Medicare Advantage**: private alternatives to Original Medicare (managed care plans, PPOs, private fee-for-service, specialty plans); may add drug, dental, and vision benefits. Requires enrollment in A and B.","**Part D — Prescription drugs**: available to anyone with Part A or Part B.","Medicare does NOT cover: **private duty nursing**, private hospital rooms (unless medically necessary), the **first 3 pints of blood**, skilled nursing beyond **100 days** per benefit period, physician charges above Medicare-approved amounts, care **outside the U.S.** (limited exceptions), **custodial care at home**, and **well care** (routine physicals, eye/hearing/dental care, immunizations, acupuncture)."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Custodial care and long-term care are the most-tested exclusions — Medicare is NOT a long-term care program. Medicaid is the program that covers custodial/nursing-home care."}]},{"heading":"Medicaid and Florida Programs","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Medicaid** is a joint **federal-state**, government-funded program for the **financially needy of any age** — applicants must demonstrate inability to afford care (means-tested on income AND assets). Unlike Medicare, Medicaid **covers custodial/assisted nursing-home care**.","**Medicaid estate planning**: Florida penalizes transferring assets below market value to qualify — eligibility can be **delayed** for transfers within the **5-year look-back period**.","**Deficit Reduction Act (DRA)** reforms gave states options: **cost sharing, flexible benefits, and healthy opportunity accounts**.","**Florida Healthy Kids Corporation** (established **1990**): expands access to health coverage for uninsured children."]}]},{"heading":"State Workers\' Compensation","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Covers **work-related injuries, illnesses, and death**; benefits include health-care costs and disability income; a goal of WC law is returning injured workers to work.","Employers provide it through a **state program**, a **private insurer**, or **self-insurance**.","Workers\' comp is **no-fault**: workers receive benefits regardless of who caused the work-related injury. All 50 states have WC laws. Employees contribute nothing."]},{"type":"tip","text":"\'Workers receive benefits only if they are not at fault\' is FALSE — workers\' comp pays regardless of fault."}]}]},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","title":"Private Insurance Plans for Seniors (Unit 21)","sections":[{"heading":"Medigap (Medicare Supplement) Policies","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Medigap** policies are **privately sold** insurance that fills the gaps in Medicare **Parts A and B** (deductibles, coinsurance). Standardized lettered plans — benefits for the same letter are identical across companies.","The NAIC **core policy (Plan A)** covers Part A coinsurance, the first **3 pints of blood** per year, and the **20% Part B coinsurance** — it does **NOT** cover the **Part A deductible**.","Someone with **Medicare Advantage does not need Medigap** — it duplicates coverage. It is **illegal to sell a Medicare Advantage plan to someone who owns a Medigap policy** (and vice versa).","**Open enrollment** — 6 months starting when the person is 65+ AND enrolled in Part B: guaranteed issue, no underwriting. Florida gives Medicare supplement buyers a **30-day free look**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Two favorite questions: Plan A core benefits do NOT include the Part A deductible, and selling duplicate coverage (MA + Medigap) is illegal."}]},{"heading":"Long-Term Care: What It Is","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Long-term care (LTC)** = a broad range of assistance for people who have lost full independence, typically needed **beyond 90 days**. Required when a person can no longer perform basic **activities of daily living (ADLs)**: feeding, toileting, bathing, dressing, walking/transferring.","**LTC insurance** pays a **set dollar benefit per day** of specified care, **without regard to actual expenses** (per-diem basis).","Covers care for **acute illness** (fully recoverable with treatment, e.g., pneumonia) and **chronic conditions** (manageable but not curable, e.g., asthma, diabetes). Alzheimer\'s, senile dementia, and Parkinson\'s ARE covered."]}]},{"heading":"Levels and Settings of Care","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Skilled nursing care** — continuous, **24-hour** care by skilled medical professionals under a physician\'s direction.","**Intermediate nursing care** — care by nurses under physician supervision, in a facility or at home, but **not round-the-clock** (periodic).","**Custodial care** — non-medical help with ADLs (bathing, dressing, eating); can be given by aides without medical training.","Specific options inside those levels: **home health care** (in the insured\'s home), **adult day care** (daytime centers while caregivers work), **alternative care** (home- and community-based services), **respite care** (short-term relief for family caregivers), and **continuing care** (in continuing-care retirement communities).","Three delivery settings: **institutional**, **home-based**, and **community** care."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Skilled vs. intermediate is tested on ONE difference: skilled = 24-hour continuous; intermediate = periodic, not 24-hour. Respite care exists to give the FAMILY CAREGIVER a break."}]},{"heading":"LTC Policy Provisions & Limits","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Benefit triggers** — the insured must be certified **chronically ill**: unable to perform at least **2 ADLs**, or needing continuous supervision for health/safety (cognitive impairment).","**Benefit limits** — coverage periods typically run **2 to 6 years**.","**Age limits** — many policies set issue-age limits around **80**, though some sell through age **89**.","**Renewability** — all LTC policies sold today must be **guaranteed renewable**.","**Elimination periods** — **0 to 365 days** before benefits begin; longer period = lower premium.","**Common exclusions** — drug and alcohol dependence, self-inflicted injuries, acts of war, and **nonorganic** mental illness.","**Premium factors** — age and health, type/level of benefits, presence and length of an elimination period, and any riders/options. (Premiums are NOT based solely on age, health, and benefit type.)"]}]},{"heading":"Group LTC, Taxation & Partnership Programs","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Group LTC** advantages: **no individual underwriting** and coverage available for **multiple family members**.","**Taxation** — LTC benefit payments are **excluded from income** (tax-free).","**State Partnership programs** — insurance-industry/state partnerships that control **Medicaid** spending while letting insureds receive benefits **without impoverishing themselves**: assets equal to the partnership policy\'s payout are disregarded when qualifying for Medicaid (Florida\'s asset-disregard \'spend-down protection\').","Florida LTC partnership policies must meet minimum standards and be at least tax-qualified, inflation-protected policies."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Partnership logic: every dollar the partnership LTC policy pays = a dollar of assets you may KEEP and still qualify for Medicaid."}]}]},{"module":"Day 6 Module 1","title":"Health Insurance Policy Provisions (Unit 22)","sections":[{"heading":"The 12 Mandatory Provisions — CLIPPERBENTG","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Every individual health insurance policy sold in Florida must include **12 mandatory provisions** drawn from the NAIC Uniform Individual Accident and Sickness Policy Provisions Law. These provisions exist to protect the insured. Insurers don\'t have to use the NAIC\'s exact wording, but any substitute language must be **at least as favorable** to the insured as the model provision. A useful mnemonic is **CLIPPERBENTG** (or G BENT CLIPPER — same letters, different order)."},{"type":"list","items":["**C — Claim forms** — the insurer must send claim forms within **15 days** of receiving notice of a claim. If it fails to do so, the insured may submit proof of loss in any written form and the insurer must still honor it. This provision keeps insurers from stalling claims by never sending paperwork.","**L — Legal actions** — the insured may sue the insurer to recover benefits, but must wait at least **60 days** after filing proof of loss before bringing suit. In Florida, the statute of limitations is **5 years** (longer than the 3-year limit used in most other states). If you see \'3 years\' as an answer on a Florida-specific exam, it\'s a trap.","**I — Incontestable clause (time limit on certain defenses)** — after the policy has been in force for **2 years**, the insurer cannot void the policy or deny claims based on misstatements in the application, **except for fraudulent misstatements**. Important: this does NOT protect against misstatement of age or sex — those are adjusted, not voided.","**P — Proof of loss** — the insured must submit written proof of loss within **90 days** of the date of loss. If the insured cannot meet the 90-day deadline for reasons beyond their control, proof submitted \'as soon as reasonably possible\' is accepted.","**P — Payment of claims** — specifies HOW and TO WHOM benefits are paid. Benefits for medical expenses may be paid to the provider. Disability income benefits are paid to the insured. If the insured dies, remaining benefits go to the designated beneficiary or the estate.","**E — Entire contract** — the policy, the attached application, and any riders together constitute the **entire agreement** between insurer and insured. Nothing may be incorporated by reference to deny a claim. After issuance, only an **executive officer** of the company (never the agent) may amend the contract.","**R — Reinstatement** — if the policy lapses for nonpayment and the insured applies to reinstate, the insurer has **45 days** to act on the application. If it takes no action within those 45 days, the policy is **automatically reinstated**. After reinstatement, **accidents are covered immediately** but **sickness only after 10 days** — this prevents people from reinstating specifically because they just got sick.","**B — Beneficiary change** — in health insurance, the insured is always the beneficiary (they receive the benefits) **except in AD&D policies**, where a death benefit beneficiary may be named. The insured can change beneficiaries at any time unless the beneficiary is designated **irrevocable**.","**E — Examination and autopsy** — the insurer has the right to examine the insured **at its own expense** as often as reasonably necessary during a claim. It may also request an autopsy in the event of death, unless prohibited by law. Key point: the **insurer pays** for every exam and autopsy it requests.","**N — Notice of claim** — the insured must notify the insurer within **20 days** of a loss (or as soon as reasonably possible). For disability claims with recurring payments, notice must be given within 20 days of each recurring loss period.","**T — Time of payment of claims** — the insurer must pay benefits **immediately** upon receiving proper proof of loss. For disability income benefits involving periodic payments, benefits must be paid at least **monthly**. In Florida specifically, the insurer has **45 days** to pay a clean claim.","**G — Grace period** — a mandatory window after the premium due date during which the policy remains in full force. The length depends on premium frequency: **7 days** (weekly premium), **10 days** (monthly premium), **31 days** (all other modes — quarterly, semi-annual, annual). If a covered loss occurs during the grace period, the insurer must pay the claim but may deduct the unpaid premium from the benefit."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The claims timeline is exam gold: **20 days** (notice of claim) → **15 days** (insurer sends claim forms) → **90 days** (proof of loss) → **immediately** upon proof (payment) → **60 days** minimum wait before suing → **5 years** to bring suit in Florida. Memorize this sequence: 20 → 15 → 90 → pay → 60 → 5 yr."}]},{"heading":"The 11 Optional (Supplementary) Provisions","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"While mandatory provisions protect the insured, the **11 optional provisions** primarily protect the insurer. The insurer may include any, all, or none of these. Understanding the distinction is critical: mandatory = insured\'s shield; optional = insurer\'s shield."},{"type":"list","items":["**Change of occupation** — if the insured switches to a **more hazardous** occupation, the insurer can reduce benefits to what the premium would have purchased at the new occupation\'s rate. If the insured switches to a **less hazardous** occupation, the insurer must reduce the premium accordingly. The adjustment works in both directions.","**Misstatement of age or sex** — if the insured\'s age or sex was stated incorrectly on the application, the insurer adjusts benefits to match what the **paid premium would have purchased at the correct age/sex**. The policy is NOT voided — benefits are simply recalculated. This is different from the incontestability provision.","**Other insurance with this insurer** — if the insured holds multiple policies with the same insurer covering the same risk, total benefits cannot exceed a set limit. This is the insurer\'s internal coordination mechanism.","**Insurance with other insurers** — similar to above, but applies when the insured has coverage with **different** insurers for the same risk. Total combined benefits are limited to actual expenses incurred — this is **coordination of benefits (COB)** in action.","**Insurance with other insurers (expense-incurred basis)** — a variation that applies specifically to expense-incurred policies: combined benefits from all insurers cannot exceed actual expenses.","**Relation of earnings to insurance** — critical for **disability income** policies. If the insured\'s total disability benefits from all sources exceed their actual earnings at the time of disability, the insurer can reduce benefits proportionally. The insurer must return the excess premium. This prevents the insured from profiting from disability.","**Unpaid premium** — any premium owed at the time of a claim may be deducted from the benefit payment. Simple but frequently tested.","**Cancellation** — grants the insurer the right to cancel the policy at any time by giving the insured **45 days\' written notice** and refunding any unearned premium. The insured can also cancel at any time by written notice.","**Conformity with state statutes** — if any provision in the policy conflicts with state law, it is automatically amended to comply. State law always wins.","**Illegal occupation** — the insurer is not liable for any loss that occurs while the insured is engaged in a **felony or illegal occupation**. If you\'re hurt during a bank robbery, your health policy won\'t cover it.","**Intoxicants and narcotics** — the insurer is not liable for any loss sustained while the insured is **under the influence of alcohol or narcotics** (unless administered on medical advice). This is one of the most common claim denials tested on the exam."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The study guide treats \'misstatement of age or sex\' as optional, but the exam often pairs it with the incontestable clause (mandatory). Key difference: incontestability is a **time-based defense** (insurer loses the right to challenge after 2 years). Misstatement of age is a **benefit-adjustment tool** (benefits are recalculated, never voided). The insurer keeps only the premium it would have charged had it known the truth."}]},{"heading":"Other Common Policy Provisions","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Insuring clause** — the insurance company\'s promise to pay. It appears on the **first page** of the policy and is signed by the company president and secretary (officers of the board). Think of it as the headline contract: \'We agree to pay the following benefits.\'","**Consideration clause** — states the premium amount, payment frequency (mode), and the effective date. NOT found on the first page — it\'s deeper in the policy. The applicant\'s consideration is the premium plus the statements made on the application.","**Conversion privilege for dependents** — in Florida, dependent conversion privileges must be offered until the dependent reaches **age 30**. This allows a dependent (typically a child aging out of a parent\'s plan) to convert to an individual policy without evidence of insurability.","**Free-look provision** — Florida mandates a **10-day** free-look period after policy delivery, during which the insured may return the policy for a full refund with no obligation. For **Medicare supplement** and **long-term care** policies, the free-look period is **30 days**. The clock starts at DELIVERY, not application.","**Preexisting condition provisions** — historically, insurers could exclude conditions that existed before the policy\'s effective date. Under the **ACA**, preexisting condition exclusions are **prohibited** in individual and small-group health plans. However, for policies not subject to the ACA (e.g., certain supplemental or grandfathered plans), preexisting condition exclusions may still apply."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Free look: 10 days standard, 30 days for Medicare supplement and LTC. The exam loves pairing these. Also note: the insuring clause (first page) vs. consideration clause (not first page) — if the question asks \'which clause appears on the first page,\' the answer is the **insuring clause**."}]},{"heading":"Common Exclusions and Limitations","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Every health insurance policy lists specific situations it will NOT cover. Exclusions define the boundaries of coverage and are one of the most-tested areas on the exam."},{"type":"list","items":["**Self-inflicted injuries** — intentional self-harm is universally excluded.","**War or act of war** — injuries sustained in declared or undeclared war.","**Aviation** — injuries sustained while serving as a **pilot or crew member** of an aircraft (passenger injuries are typically covered).","**Suicide** — generally excluded, though some policies cover it after a waiting period.","**Commission of a crime** — injuries sustained while committing or attempting to commit a **felony**.","**Military service** — injuries incurred while on active military duty (covered instead by government programs like TRICARE)."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The exam often tests whether you know the PILOT exclusion. A fare-paying airline passenger IS covered; a private pilot or crew member is NOT. If the question says \'injured while a passenger on a commercial airline,\' the exclusion does NOT apply."}]},{"heading":"Renewability Provisions","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Renewability determines who has the power to continue or end the policy. Think of it as a spectrum from most insurer-friendly to most insured-friendly. The exam tests this spectrum constantly."},{"type":"list","items":["**Cancellable** — the insurer may cancel at any time for any reason. This offers the **least** protection to the insured and is the **least expensive** policy type.","**Optionally renewable** — the insurer may choose not to renew at a premium due date or policy anniversary. More protection than cancellable, but the insurer still holds the cards at renewal time.","**Conditionally renewable** — the insurer may refuse renewal only if a specific condition listed in the policy is triggered (e.g., the insured reaches a certain age or retires). The insurer cannot refuse for health reasons alone.","**Guaranteed renewable** — the insurer MUST renew the policy until a specified age (often 65) as long as premiums are paid. The insurer CAN raise premiums, but only on a **class-wide basis** — it cannot single out one policyholder for a rate increase. **Long-term care policies are guaranteed renewable.**","**Noncancellable** — the insurer cannot cancel AND cannot raise premiums. The premium is locked in at issue. This is the **most expensive** policy type and provides the **greatest** protection to the insured."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The key distinction: **guaranteed renewable** = insurer MUST renew but CAN raise rates (class-wide). **Noncancellable** = insurer MUST renew and CANNOT raise rates. If the exam says \'premiums cannot be increased,\' the answer is **noncancellable**. If it says \'premiums can increase on a class basis,\' the answer is **guaranteed renewable**."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Can you recite the claims timeline: notice of claim → claim forms → proof of loss → payment → legal action?","What happens if the insurer fails to send claim forms within 15 days?","After reinstatement, how long must the insured wait for sickness coverage? What about accident coverage?","What is the grace period for a monthly premium policy? A quarterly policy?","How does the misstatement of age provision differ from the incontestable clause?","Rank the five renewability types from most insurer-friendly to most insured-friendly."]}]}]},{"module":"Day 6 Module 2","title":"Health Insurance Underwriting & Premiums (Unit 23)","sections":[{"heading":"Risk Factors in Health Insurance Underwriting — MOP","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Health insurance underwriting is the process of evaluating an applicant\'s risk profile to determine whether to issue a policy, and at what price. The underwriter\'s job is to classify risk accurately so the insurer can charge a premium that matches the expected cost of claims. The three **primary** risk factors are remembered with the mnemonic **MOP**."},{"type":"list","items":["**M — Moral hazard** — the applicant\'s character, lifestyle habits, and integrity. This includes drinking, drug use, personality traits, and overall way of life. Unlike physical hazards, moral hazards are about **behavior and honesty** — they\'re harder to quantify but just as important. An applicant who has filed fraudulent claims is a moral hazard.","**O — Occupation** — the nature of the applicant\'s work directly affects the probability of injury, illness, or disability. A construction worker faces higher risk than an office worker. The underwriter evaluates the occupation\'s physical demands, hazard exposure, and injury statistics.","**P — Physical condition** — the applicant\'s current health status, medical history, and family medical history. This is given the **highest priority** in underwriting. Underwriters review medical records, paramedical exams, and sometimes blood tests or attending physician statements."]},{"type":"tip","text":"MOP = Moral hazard, Occupation, Physical condition. Physical condition gets the highest priority. If the exam asks \'which factor is given the most weight in health insurance underwriting,\' the answer is **physical condition**."},{"type":"p","text":"Beyond MOP, additional risk factors influence the underwriting decision:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Age** — older applicants present higher risk because the probability of illness and disability increases with age.","**Sex** — statistically, women have higher morbidity rates than men (they tend to be disabled more often), except among the elderly where the difference narrows.","**Medical and family history** — a family history of hereditary conditions (heart disease, diabetes, cancer) elevates risk even if the applicant is currently healthy.","**Hobbies and avocations** — dangerous pastimes like skydiving, auto racing, scuba diving, or rock climbing increase the probability of accidental injury."]}]},{"heading":"Insurable Interest in Health Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Just as with life insurance, health insurance requires **insurable interest** — the applicant must face a genuine financial loss if the insured event occurs. In health insurance, insurable interest must exist **at the time of loss** (not just at application, as with life insurance). A person always has insurable interest in their own health. An employer has insurable interest in a key employee\'s health because the employee\'s disability creates a real financial loss for the business."},{"type":"tip","text":"Life insurance: insurable interest at **application**. Health insurance: insurable interest at **time of loss**. This distinction appears regularly on the exam."}]},{"heading":"Risk Classification Categories","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"After evaluating the applicant, the underwriter assigns a risk classification that determines premium rates and policy terms:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Preferred risk** — applicants in excellent health with low-risk occupations and lifestyles. They receive the **lowest** premium rates.","**Standard risk** — applicants with average health and risk profiles. They receive **typical** premium rates. Most applicants fall into this category.","**Substandard (rated) risk** — applicants with elevated risk due to health conditions, hazardous occupations, or other factors. Insurers handle substandard risks in three ways: (1) **attach an exclusion (impairment) rider** that removes specific conditions from coverage, (2) **charge an additional premium** (a \'rated-up\' or \'table-rated\' policy), or (3) **limit the types of policies** available to the applicant.","**Uninsurable (declined) risk** — the risk is too high for the insurer to accept. The applicant is declined coverage entirely."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The three substandard-risk tools are high-value exam content: **exclusion rider**, **extra premium**, **limited policy selection**. If the exam describes an applicant with a specific condition getting a policy that excludes that condition, the tool being used is an **impairment (exclusion) rider**."}]},{"heading":"Premium Factors — MIX","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Three primary factors determine the cost of a health insurance premium. Use the mnemonic **MIX**:"},{"type":"list","items":["**M — Morbidity** — the statistical probability that a person of a given age will become sick or disabled. Morbidity tables are the health insurance equivalent of mortality tables in life insurance. Higher morbidity = higher premiums.","**I — Interest (investment income)** — insurers invest a portion of every premium dollar. The expected return on those investments offsets the cost of future claims, allowing premiums to be lower than they would be if the insurer relied solely on premium revenue. When interest rates are high, premiums can be lower.","**X — Expenses (loading)** — the insurer\'s operating costs: commissions, administrative overhead, salaries, marketing, taxes, and profit margin. These costs are \'loaded\' on top of the pure cost of expected claims."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Health insurance premiums use **morbidity**; life insurance premiums use **mortality**. If the exam asks \'which table is used to determine health insurance premiums,\' the answer is a **morbidity table**. Both use interest and expenses — the distinguishing factor is morbidity vs. mortality."}]},{"heading":"Tax Treatment of Health Insurance Premiums and Benefits","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Tax rules for health insurance follow a general principle: **if you paid the premium with after-tax dollars, the benefits are tax-free; if someone else paid (or you deducted the premium), the benefits may be taxable.** Here are the key rules:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Disability income insurance** — when premiums are paid personally with **after-tax dollars**, the disability income benefits are received **tax-free**. When the **employer** pays the premiums, the benefits are **taxable income** to the employee. This is the classic \'who pays the premium?\' tax question.","**Medical expense insurance** — reimbursed medical expenses are NOT eligible for a tax deduction (you can\'t deduct an expense that was already reimbursed). Unreimbursed medical expenses may be deductible only to the extent they exceed **10% of adjusted gross income (AGI)** under current IRS rules.","**Employer-paid group health premiums** — the employer\'s premium contributions are **tax-deductible** for the employer as a business expense and are **not counted as taxable income** to the employee. This double tax advantage is why group health insurance is so prevalent."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The tax question students miss most: \'An employee\'s disability income benefits are taxable if ____.\' The answer is \'the employer paid the premiums.\' If the employee paid, benefits are tax-free. Whoever pays the premium determines the tax treatment of the benefit."}]},{"heading":"Managed Care Organizations (MCOs)","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Managed care** is a system of healthcare delivery designed to control costs while maintaining quality. MCOs use various strategies to manage utilization and negotiate lower provider rates. The four general approaches to cost containment form the mnemonic **MACP**:"},{"type":"list","items":["**M — Mandatory second opinions** — requiring a second physician\'s opinion before approving expensive procedures (e.g., surgery) to prevent unnecessary treatments.","**A — Ambulatory (outpatient) surgery** — encouraging procedures to be performed on an outpatient basis when medically safe, avoiding the higher cost of inpatient hospitalization.","**C — Case management** — a specialist (usually a nurse or social worker) affiliated with the insurer reviews the insured\'s treatment plan and recommends alternative, cost-effective treatments. The case manager coordinates care across providers.","**P — Precertification (preadmission review)** — requiring approval from the insurer BEFORE a hospital admission or major procedure. If the insured skips precertification, benefits may be reduced or denied."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The exam defines the purpose of managed care as managing and regulating **health claims expenses** — not discouraging people from seeking care. If you see \'discouraging individuals from seeking health care\' as an answer, it\'s the planted wrong choice."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Name the three primary risk factors (MOP) and explain which gets the most weight.","What are the four risk classification categories, and what are the three tools for handling substandard risks?","Name the three premium factors (MIX) and explain how morbidity differs from mortality.","If an employer pays the premium for an employee\'s disability income policy, are the benefits taxable to the employee?","What are the four managed care cost-containment strategies (MACP)?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 6 Module 3","title":"Group Health Insurance (Unit 24)","sections":[{"heading":"Nature and Structure of Group Health Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Approximately **90% of Americans with private health insurance** are covered through employer-sponsored group plans. Group health insurance fundamentally differs from individual insurance in structure, cost, and underwriting approach."},{"type":"list","items":["**Master policy** — the employer (or group sponsor) holds the master contract. The master policy contains the full terms, conditions, and benefit schedules. Individual employees do NOT hold the policy itself.","**Certificate of insurance** — each covered employee receives a certificate that summarizes the coverage terms. The certificate is evidence of coverage, not the contract itself.","**Group must be \'natural\'** — the group must exist for a purpose OTHER than obtaining insurance (e.g., an employer-employee relationship, a professional association, a labor union). A group formed solely to buy insurance is not eligible.","**No minimum size in Florida** — unlike many states, Florida does **not** set a minimum number of participants or a minimum participation percentage for issuing group health insurance. This is a Florida-specific detail the exam may test."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Master policy = employer holds it. Certificate = employee gets it. If the exam asks \'who holds the group insurance contract,\' the answer is the employer/policyholder, not the individual employee."}]},{"heading":"Eligibility, Contributory vs. Noncontributory","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Before an employee can participate in a group health plan, certain eligibility conditions must typically be met: the employee must work **full-time** and may need to complete a **probationary period** (usually 1 to 3 months). Once eligible, the employee must enroll during the enrollment window or risk having to wait and potentially undergo individual underwriting."},{"type":"list","items":["**Contributory plan** — both the employer and employees share the premium cost. Because participation is voluntary (employees might decline), a minimum of **75% of eligible employees** must participate to prevent adverse selection.","**Noncontributory plan** — the employer pays **100%** of the premium. Because there is no cost to employees, **100%** of eligible employees must be enrolled. This eliminates adverse selection entirely since everyone is covered regardless of health status."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Contributory = 75% participation required. Noncontributory = 100% participation required. The higher the employer\'s share, the higher the required participation rate. This is counterintuitive until you realize: noncontributory plans REQUIRE everyone because the employer is already paying — there\'s no reason to opt out unless you\'re hiding something (adverse selection)."}]},{"heading":"Group Underwriting and Cost Advantages","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Group underwriting** — the insurer evaluates the **group as a whole**, not individual members. No individual evidence of insurability is required for eligible employees who enroll on time. This is the defining feature that makes group insurance accessible to people who might not qualify for individual coverage.","**Florida large-group rule** — for groups of **51 or more employees**, Florida law requires the insurer to accept the **entire group** — it cannot cherry-pick healthy members and exclude others.","**Lower per-person cost** — group plans have lower administrative costs per person because one policy covers many people, reducing underwriting, billing, and marketing expenses. Economies of scale make group coverage consistently cheaper than equivalent individual coverage.","**Predetermined benefits** — benefit levels are set by the employer in conjunction with the insurer\'s benefit schedules. Individual employees do not negotiate their own benefit terms.","**Preexisting conditions under ACA** — for plans subject to the **Affordable Care Act**, preexisting condition exclusions are **prohibited**. For non-ACA plans, **HIPAA** governs portability and limits on preexisting condition exclusions."]}]},{"heading":"Types of Group Health Coverage","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Group basic medical expense** — covers three categories of routine care: **hospital expenses** (room, board, ancillary services), **surgical expenses** (surgeon and anesthesiologist fees), and **physician expenses** (non-surgical doctor visits).","**Group major medical expense** — provides broader, more comprehensive coverage for catastrophic medical costs. Comes in two forms: **comprehensive major medical** (single policy covering both basic and major medical) and **supplemental major medical** (supplements a separate basic medical plan, covering costs that exceed the basic plan\'s limits).","**Coordination of benefits (COB)** — a provision found **exclusively in group health plans** that prevents duplicate payments when an insured is covered by more than one group plan. COB identifies which plan is **primary** (pays first) and which is **secondary** (pays remaining eligible expenses up to the total bill). The **birthday rule** determines primary coverage for dependent children: the plan of the parent whose birthday falls earlier in the **calendar year** (month and day only — NOT by age) is primary.","**Group short-term disability** — provides income replacement for **13 to 26 weeks** (roughly 3 to 6 months) of disability.","**Group long-term disability** — provides income replacement for disabilities lasting **more than 2 years**, often until age 65. Long-term disability benefits typically don\'t begin until short-term benefits have been exhausted — the two do NOT pay simultaneously."]},{"type":"tip","text":"COB birthday rule: it\'s the parent whose birthday is **earlier in the calendar year**, not the older parent. A parent born January 15 is primary over a parent born March 1, regardless of birth year. This is the #1 COB exam trap."}]},{"heading":"COBRA — Continuation of Group Coverage","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"The **Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act (COBRA)** is a federal law that allows employees and their dependents to **continue** group health coverage at their own expense after a qualifying event that would otherwise end their coverage."},{"type":"list","items":["**Applies to employers with 20 or more employees** — smaller employers are exempt from federal COBRA (but Florida\'s mini-COBRA applies to them).","**18 months** — the standard continuation period for **employment termination** (other than gross misconduct) or **reduction in hours**.","**29 months** — if the qualified beneficiary is **disabled** (as determined by Social Security) at the time of the qualifying event, coverage extends to 29 months. The premium for months 19–29 can be up to **150%** of the group rate.","**36 months** — for events affecting **dependents**: death of the employee, divorce or legal separation, the employee becoming entitled to Medicare, or a dependent child aging out of coverage.","**Premium** — the former employee may be required to pay up to **102%** of the full group premium (the extra 2% covers administration). The employer does NOT have to contribute.","**Florida mini-COBRA** — Florida\'s Health Insurance Coverage Continuation Act (§627.6692) extends similar continuation rights to employees of **small employers (fewer than 20 employees)** for generally **18 months**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"COBRA durations: **18** = job loss/reduced hours. **29** = disability extension. **36** = dependent events (death, divorce, Medicare, aging out). Premium can be **102%** (standard) or **150%** (disability extension months 19–29). If the question says \'15-employee company,\' federal COBRA does NOT apply — **Florida mini-COBRA** does."}]},{"heading":"Other Group Health Products","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Group AD&D** — accidental death and dismemberment coverage provided through the employer. Unlike group life and group medical, **AD&D generally does NOT offer a conversion privilege**. This is a frequently tested distinction.","**Blanket health policies** — cover an entire group exposed to the **same risks**, where the membership is constantly changing. Classic examples: an airline covering all passengers, a school covering all students, a bus company covering all riders. The key feature is that individuals in the group change continuously — no individual underwriting, no individual certificates.","**Franchise (wholesale) policies** — individual policies sold to members of an association or professional society at group-discounted rates. Each member gets their own individual policy, unlike a true group plan with a master contract.","**Credit accident and health insurance** — pays the insured\'s loan or debt payments if the borrower becomes disabled. The creditor (lender) is the beneficiary.","**Health savings accounts (HSAs)** — tax-advantaged savings accounts paired with a **high-deductible health plan (HDHP)**. Eligibility requires being under **age 65** and enrolled in an HDHP. Contributions are limited annually. Earnings grow **tax-free** and withdrawals for qualified medical expenses are **tax-free**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Group AD&D = NO conversion privilege. Group life = HAS conversion privilege. This is a classic exam pair. Also: blanket policies cover groups that constantly change (think passengers), franchise policies cover stable associations (think professional groups)."}]},{"heading":"Group Health Plan Tax Treatment","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Group health insurance enjoys favorable tax treatment that incentivizes employers to offer coverage:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Employer premium contributions** are **tax-deductible** as a business expense for the employer.","**Employee benefit**: employer-paid group health premiums are **NOT counted as taxable income** to the employee. This means the employee receives a valuable benefit without increasing their tax burden.","**Employee contributions** to group plans may be made **pre-tax** through a Section 125 cafeteria plan, further reducing taxable income.","**Individual contributions** to group medical plans can be included in the medical expense deduction only when total unreimbursed medical expenses exceed **10% of AGI**."]}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["What is the participation requirement for a contributory group plan vs. a noncontributory plan?","Who holds the master policy and what do employees receive?","What are the three COBRA continuation periods, and which qualifying events trigger each?","How does the birthday rule determine primary coverage for dependent children?","Name a group health product that does NOT offer a conversion privilege.","What makes Florida\'s group insurance rules different regarding minimum group size?"]}]}]},{"module":"Day 6 Module 4","title":"Uses of Health Insurance (Unit 25)","sections":[{"heading":"How Individuals Use Health Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Health insurance serves two fundamental purposes for individuals: **medical expense protection** (covering the cost of healthcare) and **income replacement** (replacing lost earnings during disability). Understanding both dimensions — and the gap between what people think they have and what they actually need — is essential for both the exam and professional practice."},{"type":"list","items":["**Group coverage is more common than individual** — group policies cover the vast majority of privately insured Americans because they offer broader coverage at lower cost, require no individual underwriting, and include a **conversion privilege** as a safety net when employment ends.","**Lower out-of-pocket costs** — group plans typically have lower deductibles, lower coinsurance, and higher benefit maximums compared to individual policies, making them more comprehensive.","**Disability income insurance is commonly overlooked** — many people assume Social Security disability benefits will be sufficient to replace their income if they become disabled. In reality, Social Security disability has a strict definition of disability (\'inability to engage in any substantial gainful activity\'), a 5-month waiting period, and benefits that replace only a fraction of pre-disability income. Private disability income insurance fills this critical gap.","**Paid family leave insurance** — some employers purchase paid family leave coverage that pays a **percentage of the employee\'s income** during leave taken for the birth of a child, adoption, or care of a seriously ill family member."]},{"type":"tip","text":"If the exam asks \'which offers broader coverage, group or individual health insurance,\' the answer is **group**. Group plans cover more people, cost less per person, and include protections (like guaranteed issue and conversion privileges) that individual plans typically don\'t."}]},{"heading":"How Businesses Use Health Insurance — Employee Benefits","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Employers use health insurance strategically, not just as an employee benefit but as a business tool. Offering health coverage serves multiple business purposes:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Competitive hiring advantage** — health benefits are a key factor in attracting and retaining qualified employees in a competitive labor market.","**Employee morale and productivity** — employees with reliable health coverage are less stressed about medical costs, leading to higher engagement and lower absenteeism.","**Tax deductions** — employer contributions to group health plans are **deductible as a business expense**, reducing the company\'s taxable income.","**Cafeteria plans (Section 125)** — these plans offer employees a **menu of benefits** to choose from (dental, vision, short-term disability, FSA, HSA contributions, etc.). Employees select the benefits that best fit their needs and pay for them with **pre-tax dollars**, reducing both the employee\'s taxable income and the employer\'s payroll tax liability. Once an election is made, it is generally **irrevocable** for the plan year unless the employee experiences a qualifying life event (marriage, birth, divorce)."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Cafeteria plans = **choice** from a menu of benefits + **pre-tax** payment. The name says it all — employees pick what they want from the \'cafeteria line.\' Section 125 is the IRC section that authorizes them."}]},{"heading":"Business Overhead Expense (BOE) Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Business overhead expense (BOE) insurance** is a specialized disability policy that pays the **fixed operating expenses** of a business when the owner becomes disabled and cannot work. It keeps the lights on — literally — while the owner recovers."},{"type":"list","items":["**Covered expenses** — rent or mortgage, utilities, telephone/internet, leased equipment payments, **employees\' salaries**, business insurance premiums, and similar fixed operating costs.","**NOT covered** — the **owner\'s personal salary or income**. This is the single most-tested BOE fact. BOE protects the business, not the owner\'s personal finances. For personal income replacement, the owner needs a separate disability income policy.","**Tax treatment** — BOE premiums are **tax-deductible** as a business expense (because they cover business costs), but the benefits received are **taxable income** to the business. This is opposite from personal disability income, where premiums are NOT deductible but benefits ARE tax-free."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The #1 BOE exam question: \'Which expense would NOT be covered under a BOE policy?\' The answer is always **the owner\'s salary**. BOE pays employees\' salaries, rent, and utilities — everything the business needs to survive — but NOT the owner\'s personal draw."}]},{"heading":"Disability Buyout Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Disability buyout insurance** funds the purchase of a disabled co-owner\'s share of a business. It works alongside a **buy-sell agreement** — a pre-arranged contract that specifies the terms under which one partner\'s ownership interest will be bought out by the remaining partners if that partner becomes permanently disabled."},{"type":"list","items":["**Purpose** — provides the cash needed to execute the buyout without forcing the healthy partners to liquidate assets or take on debt. It ensures a clean, orderly ownership transition.","**Lump sum option** — many disability buyout policies offer the option to receive the benefit as a **lump sum payment** rather than monthly installments, enabling an immediate buyout.","**Longer elimination period** — because buyouts are intended for **permanent** disability (not temporary), these policies typically have longer elimination periods (often 12–24 months) compared to standard disability income policies.","**Key difference from BOE** — BOE covers **ongoing monthly expenses** to keep the business running during a temporary disability. Disability buyout addresses **permanent** disability by funding the **transfer of ownership**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"BOE = keep the business alive during temporary disability (monthly operating costs). Disability buyout = transfer ownership permanently (lump sum or structured buyout). If the exam describes a partner who will never return to work and the remaining partners need to buy the disabled partner out, the answer is **disability buyout insurance**."}]},{"heading":"Key Person Disability Insurance","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**Key person disability insurance** protects a business against the financial impact of losing a **critical employee** to disability. The employee doesn\'t have to be an owner — they just need to be someone whose absence would cause measurable financial harm to the company."},{"type":"list","items":["**The business is the owner and beneficiary** — the business purchases the policy, pays the premiums, and receives the benefits. The key employee is the insured but does not receive the money.","**Monthly benefit** — unlike key person life insurance (which pays a lump sum at death), key person disability insurance pays a **monthly benefit** for as long as the key employee is disabled, helping the company cover the cost of lost revenue, temporary replacements, or recruitment.","**Parallel to key person life insurance** — just as key person life insurance covers the financial loss from a key employee\'s death, key person disability covers the loss from their inability to work. The structure mirrors life insurance but addresses a much more common event — statistically, long-term disability is far more likely than premature death during working years."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Three business disability products, three different purposes: **BOE** = pays business overhead. **Disability buyout** = buys out a disabled partner\'s ownership share. **Key person disability** = compensates the company for losing a vital employee. Know which product matches which scenario — the exam gives you a business situation and expects you to pick the right product."}]},{"heading":"Reducing Premium Costs","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Both individuals and businesses can take steps to lower health insurance premium costs without sacrificing essential coverage. Understanding these strategies is practical for client advising and tested on the exam."},{"type":"list","items":["**Increase the deductible** — a higher deductible means the insured absorbs more of the initial cost before insurance kicks in, resulting in lower premiums.","**Extend the elimination (waiting) period** — for disability income policies, a longer waiting period before benefits begin translates to lower premiums. A 90-day elimination period is cheaper than a 30-day one.","**Modify benefit amounts** — reducing the maximum benefit or daily benefit amount lowers the premium.","**NOT a valid strategy**: waiving the right to receive benefits. You cannot reduce premiums by agreeing not to collect benefits — that defeats the purpose of insurance."]},{"type":"tip","text":"The exam\'s trap answer for \'how to reduce premiums\' is always \'waive the right to receive benefits.\' That\'s never a real strategy. The legitimate methods are: raise the deductible, extend the elimination period, and reduce benefit amounts."}]},{"heading":"Quick Self-Check","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Why is group health insurance preferred over individual coverage for most people?","What is a cafeteria plan and what tax advantage does it offer?","What expenses does BOE insurance cover, and what critical expense does it NOT cover?","How does disability buyout insurance differ from BOE insurance?","Who is the owner and beneficiary of a key person disability policy?","Name three legitimate ways to reduce health insurance premium costs."]}]}]},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","category":"Coming Up Next","title":"Health Policy Provisions, Clauses & Riders","sections":[{"heading":"The Uniform Provisions Framework","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Every individual health policy sold in Florida must contain a set of **mandatory provisions** (12 of them, from the NAIC Uniform Individual Accident and Sickness Policy Provisions Law, adopted in FL Statutes ch. 627) and may include certain **optional provisions**. Mandatory provisions protect the insured; optional provisions mostly protect the insurer. The numbers below are exam gold."},{"type":"list","items":["**Entire contract** — the policy plus attached application is the whole agreement; nothing can be incorporated by reference, and only an executive officer (never the agent) can change it.","**Time limit on certain defenses (incontestability)** — after **2 years**, the insurer cannot void the policy or deny a claim for misstatements on the application, except fraudulent misstatements.","**Misstatement of age** — if the insured\'s age was misstated, benefits are adjusted to what the premium would have bought at the true age — the policy is not voided."]}]},{"heading":"Grace Periods and Reinstatement","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Grace period** depends on premium mode: **7 days** (weekly), **10 days** (monthly), **31 days** (all other modes). Coverage stays in force during the grace period.","**Reinstatement** — if the insurer requires an application and issues a conditional receipt, the policy is automatically reinstated on the **45th day** unless the insurer disapproves in writing first.","A reinstated policy covers **accidents immediately**, but **sickness only after 10 days** — this blocks people from reinstating because they just got sick."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Memorize the trio 7 / 10 / 31 for grace periods and 45 / 10 for reinstatement. These exact numbers appear on the state exam constantly."}]},{"heading":"The Claims Clock","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"A chain of deadlines governs every claim. In order:"},{"type":"list","items":["**Notice of claim** — insured must notify the insurer within **20 days** of loss (or as soon as reasonably possible).","**Claim forms** — insurer must send forms within **15 days** of notice; if it doesn\'t, the insured may submit proof in any written form.","**Proof of loss** — insured must file within **90 days** of the loss.","**Time of payment of claims** — payable immediately on proof; disability income benefits must be paid at least **monthly**.","**Legal actions** — the insured must wait at least **60 days** after proof of loss before suing, and in Florida has up to **5 years** to bring suit."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Sequence mnemonic: 20 → 15 → 90 → pay → 60. Florida\'s 5-year legal action limit is longer than the 3-year limit used in many other states — Florida-specific answers win on a Florida exam."}]},{"heading":"Free Look and Common Riders","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Free look** — Florida health policies give **10 days** to return the policy for a full refund; **Medicare supplement and long-term care policies get 30 days**.","**Impairment (exclusion) rider** — excludes a named preexisting condition from coverage; lets an otherwise uninsurable applicant get a policy.","**Guaranteed insurability rider** — buy more coverage later without proving insurability.","**Multiple indemnity / accident riders** — increase benefits for specific accident types."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Free look starts at DELIVERY. 10 days standard, 30 days for Medicare supplement and LTC — a favorite trick pairing."}]}]},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","category":"Coming Up Next","title":"Group Health Insurance, COBRA & Continuation","sections":[{"heading":"How Group Coverage Works","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["The employer holds the **master contract**; employees receive **certificates of insurance**.","Underwriting is on the GROUP as a whole — no individual evidence of insurability for eligible employees who enroll on time.","**Eligibility** — full-time employees, often after a probationary period; enroll during the eligibility/open-enrollment window or wait (and possibly face underwriting).","**Conversion privilege** — an employee leaving the group can convert to an individual policy within **31 days** without proving insurability (premiums are higher)."]},{"type":"tip","text":"No individual underwriting is the defining feature of group insurance — adverse selection is controlled by the group\'s natural composition and enrollment windows."}]},{"heading":"COBRA","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"**COBRA** (federal) applies to employers with **20 or more employees** and lets covered persons keep group coverage at their own expense — up to **102%** of the group premium — after a qualifying event."},{"type":"list","items":["**18 months** — employment termination (other than gross misconduct) or reduction in hours.","**29 months** — if the qualified beneficiary is disabled (Social Security definition) at the time of the event.","**36 months** — events affecting dependents: death of the employee, divorce, Medicare entitlement, or a child aging out."]},{"type":"tip","text":"18 = job loss. 29 = disabled. 36 = dependent events. And the premium can be 102% — the extra 2% covers administration."}]},{"heading":"Florida Continuation (Mini-COBRA)","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Florida\'s **Health Insurance Coverage Continuation Act** (§627.6692) extends similar continuation rights to employees of SMALL employers (fewer than 20 employees) that federal COBRA doesn\'t reach — generally **18 months** of continuation after a qualifying event. The employee must elect and pay timely."},{"type":"tip","text":"If the question says \'15-employee company\' and asks about continuation, federal COBRA does NOT apply — Florida\'s continuation act does."}]},{"heading":"Coordination of Benefits","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["When a person is covered by two plans, **COB rules** decide which pays first so combined payment never exceeds 100% of the claim.","The employee\'s own plan is **primary** for the employee.","For dependent children covered under both parents\' plans, the **birthday rule** applies: the plan of the parent whose birthday falls earlier in the calendar YEAR is primary (month and day — not age)."]}]}]},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","category":"Coming Up Next","title":"Florida Licensing, Regulation & Market Conduct","sections":[{"heading":"Who Regulates What","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**DFS (Department of Financial Services)** — headed by the elected **Chief Financial Officer (CFO)**; licenses and disciplines AGENTS, investigates agent misconduct, handles consumer complaints.","**OIR (Office of Insurance Regulation)** — regulates INSURERS: issues certificates of authority, approves forms and rates, examines insurer finances.","The state legislature makes insurance law; DFS and OIR administer and enforce it."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Agents answer to DFS; companies answer to OIR. If the question involves a license discipline, think DFS; if it involves policy form approval, think OIR."}]},{"heading":"Getting and Keeping the 2-40 License","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Qualifications** — at least 18, Florida resident, fingerprints/background check, complete an approved **40-hour** prelicensing course, pass the state exam.","**Appointment** — you can\'t transact until an insurer appoints you; appointments renew every 24 months. A license **terminates after 4 years (48 months) without any appointment**.","**Continuing education** — **24 hours every 2 years** (drops to **20 hours** once licensed 6+ years), including a required law-and-ethics update course.","Notify DFS of changes of name, address, or email promptly."]},{"type":"tip","text":"40 prelicensing hours, 24 CE hours per 2 years (20 after 6 years licensed), 4-year appointment rule. Numbers carry these questions."}]},{"heading":"Money and Fiduciary Duty","blocks":[{"type":"p","text":"Premiums an agent collects are **trust funds** held in a fiduciary capacity — they belong to the insurer (or the insured, for return premiums), never to the agent. Commingling premium money with personal funds, or failing to remit it, is grounds for license action and can be prosecuted as **misappropriation**, a criminal offense."}]},{"heading":"Prohibited Practices, Florida-Style","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["**Misrepresentation** — false statements about a policy\'s terms, benefits, or dividends.","**Twisting** — inducing replacement with a DIFFERENT insurer through misrepresentation. **Churning** — same scheme, SAME insurer.","**Sliding** — charging for or attaching extra products the buyer didn\'t agree to (e.g., adding an ancillary product to every sale \'automatically\').","**Defamation** — false, malicious statements injurious to another insurer.","**Coercion / boycott / intimidation** — anticompetitive pressure to buy.","**Rebating** — legal in Florida ONLY under §626.572: the rebate must come from the agent\'s commission, be available to all insureds in the same actuarial class, and follow a filed schedule.","**Fraud** — knowingly false statements on applications or claims; insurance fraud is a **felony**."]},{"type":"tip","text":"Twisting vs. churning vs. sliding: different insurer / same insurer / unwanted extras. Florida is unusual on rebating — conditionally legal, so \'rebating is always illegal\' is a WRONG answer on a Florida exam."}]},{"heading":"Doing Business Right","blocks":[{"type":"list","items":["Only **licensed and appointed** persons may transact insurance; unlicensed transaction is criminal.","Advertising must be truthful; using \'free insurance\' as an inducement is prohibited.","Agents must keep records of transactions available to DFS.","Penalties scale from fines and probation to suspension and **revocation** (and after revocation, a waiting period before reapplying)."]}]}]}]')}]);